00:21:08,017 --> 00:21:10,852
- I was only working for Kastner at the time.
- Yeah, right.

441
00:21:16,067 --> 00:21:17,943
CHAMPLIN: Bye.
- Take care.

442
00:21:18,110 --> 00:21:20,779
- Who's that?
- Uh, an exec over at Fox.

443
00:21:20,947 --> 00:21:22,989
- Or was until this breakfast anyways.
- Yeah.

444
00:21:31,707 --> 00:21:36,294
- Morning, Mr. Mill. Welcome to Geoffrey's.
- Hi, Susan. How are you? I'm with Joel.

445
00:21:37,046 --> 00:21:38,296
GRIFFIN:
Hi, Burt. Griffin Mill.

446
00:21:38,464 --> 00:21:40,006
- Good to see you.
- Good to see you.

447
00:21:40,216 --> 00:21:42,384
Griffin. Nice to see you this morning.
Bye-bye.

448
00:21:42,551 --> 00:21:46,262
REYNOLDS: Asshole.
- Ha, ha. One of a breed, yes.

449
00:21:46,973 --> 00:21:50,016
Actually, he's not one of a breed.
There's a whole breed of them.

450
00:21:50,184 --> 00:21:52,894
- They're breeding them actually.
GRIFFIN: You're losing your touch.

451
00:21:53,062 --> 00:21:57,065
Scheduling these meetings so close together.
Guy didn't have time to finish breakfast.

452
00:21:57,233 --> 00:22:00,318
LEVISON: He'd already eaten. Gets up early.
GRIFFIN: Yeah.

453
00:22:00,486 --> 00:22:03,822
LEVISON: You went to Mellen's last night.
- Would you take this away? Yes, I did.

454
00:22:03,990 --> 00:22:06,616
LEVISON: How is he?
- I would like a Vittel water.

455
00:22:07,743 --> 00:22:09,661
He's fine.

456
00:22:09,912 --> 00:22:11,913
You left early, why?

457
00:22:12,206 --> 00:22:15,750
We had to work on the, uh...
On the museum party.

458
00:22:16,252 --> 00:22:18,795
I will not work for Larry Levy.

459
00:22:19,005 --> 00:22:21,089
I'm not asking you to.

460
00:22:22,591 --> 00:22:26,428
I report to you.
If I have to report to Larry Levy, I quit.

461
00:22:28,389 --> 00:22:29,806
You can't quit.

462
00:22:30,016 --> 00:22:33,393
I won't let you quit.
You have a year and a half on your contract.

463
00:22:33,561 --> 00:22:38,690
And I will sue you for breach if you don't
show up in the office every day with a smile.

464
00:22:39,400 --> 00:22:41,234
Why Levy?

465
00:22:41,694 --> 00:22:46,531
Levy was available. He's good on
material, you're good with writers.

466
00:22:46,699 --> 00:22:50,201
We're a team. He's a new member
of the team, that's all.

467
00:22:50,369 --> 00:22:53,747
- He can make us all look good.
- This is a red-wine glass.

468
00:22:53,914 --> 00:22:56,708
Can I have my water
in a water glass, please?

469
00:22:57,084 --> 00:22:58,460
Well?

470
00:22:59,170 --> 00:23:01,588
I'll have to think about it, Joel.

471
00:23:01,797 --> 00:23:03,506
I want an answer this afternoon.

472
00:23:03,841 --> 00:23:06,176
Well, I have to go out to Palmdale.

473
00:23:06,385 --> 00:23:09,846
The director of The Lonely Room
is giving Lily a hard time.

474
00:23:10,556 --> 00:23:11,848
I'll be back around 5.

475
00:23:12,058 --> 00:23:15,185
- So call after 5.
- I'll get back to you.

476
00:23:15,352 --> 00:23:18,772
REYNOLDS: But I said, "You know, you
haven't gone... You haven't died enough."

477
00:23:18,939 --> 00:23:20,857
So he's still hanging on.

478
00:23:32,161 --> 00:23:33,203
[INTERCOM BEEPS]

479
00:23:33,370 --> 00:23:34,788
JAN [OVER INTERCOM]: Griffin.
- Yeah.

480
00:23:34,955 --> 00:23:37,749
- Joel Levison on Line 2. Put him through?
- No. I'll get back to him.

481
00:23:37,917 --> 00:23:39,667
Tell Joel Levison
you'll get back to him?

482
00:23:39,835 --> 00:23:41,294
- Yeah.
- Yes, sir.

483
00:23:41,462 --> 00:23:43,713
I wanna hear what he's gotta say.

484
00:23:53,057 --> 00:23:56,017
GRIFFIN: How did this get here?
- The mail.

485
00:23:56,227 --> 00:23:59,020
But this does not have a postmark.
This was hand-delivered.

486
00:23:59,355 --> 00:24:02,774
Not to me. It came with the mail.
Jimmy?

487
00:24:03,192 --> 00:24:04,692
JIMMY:
Huh?

488
00:24:05,152 --> 00:24:08,238
You know anything about this?
Who delivered it, where it came from?

489
00:24:09,532 --> 00:24:10,573
Mailroom?

490
00:24:10,783 --> 00:24:13,201
But I wanna know how it got
to the goddamn mailroom.

491
00:24:13,369 --> 00:24:15,161
Find out for me and get back to me.

492
00:24:15,329 --> 00:24:17,038
- Okay, sure.
- You go with him.

493
00:24:18,124 --> 00:24:21,376
- You want me to go to the mailroom?
- Yes. I want you to go to the mailroom.

494
00:24:21,544 --> 00:24:25,755
And while you're there, I would like a, uh,
copy of The Lonely Room rewrites.

495
00:24:25,965 --> 00:24:28,299
In white pages, no color.

496
00:24:28,551 --> 00:24:31,094
- And find out how this got in my mail.
- Yes, sir.

497
00:24:31,470 --> 00:24:35,557
- You'll get your own phones, I take it?
- Yes, I can get my own phone, Jan.

498
00:24:42,022 --> 00:24:43,940
Son of a bitch. Five months.

499
00:24:44,108 --> 00:24:48,862
One, two, three, four, five. April.

500
00:24:50,447 --> 00:24:52,323
"Pitches. Richard Fielder, David Lucas...

501
00:24:52,491 --> 00:24:54,033
[DOOR CLOSES]

502
00:24:54,201 --> 00:24:55,577
...Adam Silverstein...

503
00:24:56,787 --> 00:24:58,580
...Bill Lindstrom, David Kahane...

504
00:24:58,747 --> 00:25:00,874
...Sandra Potenza."

505
00:25:06,255 --> 00:25:08,214
Incoming.

506
00:25:11,594 --> 00:25:14,971
Incoming. Unreturned calls.

507
00:25:15,181 --> 00:25:17,932
Bill Lindstrom again.

508
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:22,395
Nancy Franklin. Wouldn't be a woman.
Wouldn't be a woman. David Kahane.

509
00:25:24,106 --> 00:25:28,693
Oh, come on. Sort, sort, sort. Come on.

510
00:25:31,155 --> 00:25:34,991
Come on. Kahane, Kahane, Kahane.
Lindstrom. Lindstrom. White pages.

511
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:40,205
Lindstrom. Disney, strategic planning.

512
00:25:40,372 --> 00:25:44,459
It wouldn't be him.
And what was that other guy's name?

513
00:25:44,960 --> 00:25:48,421
Kahane. Kahane. J-K.

514
00:25:48,631 --> 00:25:50,465
"Kalchime.

515
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:52,133
Kahane."

516
00:25:52,343 --> 00:25:54,427
Unproduced. Got you!

517
00:26:19,328 --> 00:26:21,162
[DIAL TONE]

518
00:26:21,330 --> 00:26:23,289
[DIALING]

519
00:26:29,296 --> 00:26:31,339
[PHONE RINGING]

520
00:26:52,194 --> 00:26:55,321
JUNE [ON PHONE]: Hello?
- Yes. Is David Kahane there, please?

521
00:26:55,531 --> 00:26:56,572
JUNE:
David?

522
00:27:01,245 --> 00:27:02,870
Dave?

523
00:27:04,039 --> 00:27:06,916
Hello? I'm really sorry, I forgot.
He's gone out.

524
00:27:07,126 --> 00:27:08,376
GRIFFIN: Oh, I see.
- Who's this?

525
00:27:08,585 --> 00:27:10,420
This is Griffin Mill.

526
00:27:10,713 --> 00:27:14,090
- Oh, the dead man.
- What did you just say?

527
00:27:14,300 --> 00:27:16,759
- About... About me being a dead man.
- Oh, nothing.

528
00:27:17,011 --> 00:27:20,805
Just a nickname David has for you.

529
00:27:21,015 --> 00:27:24,684
Oh, I see. That's a funny nickname.

530
00:27:24,977 --> 00:27:28,354
So I suppose your husband
doesn't like me very much.

531
00:27:28,897 --> 00:27:30,940
I don't have a husband.

532
00:27:31,108 --> 00:27:33,192
I suppose David doesn't like me
very much.

533
00:27:33,360 --> 00:27:35,611
David's, uh, gone to the cinema.

534
00:27:35,821 --> 00:27:37,447
When will he be back?

535
00:27:37,656 --> 00:27:39,657
When the film's over, I presume.

536
00:27:39,867 --> 00:27:42,160
And you are?

537
00:27:42,786 --> 00:27:45,371
- June.
- June...

538
00:27:45,581 --> 00:27:47,790
Here we go.
You want to know my last name.

539
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:50,084
You won't be able to pronounce it.
No one can.

540
00:27:50,252 --> 00:27:53,338
- Try me.
- Gudmundsdottir.

541
00:27:53,547 --> 00:27:54,881
Goodmanzdaughter.

542
00:27:55,090 --> 00:27:58,259
- Gudmundsdottir.
- Gudmundsdottir.

543
00:27:58,469 --> 00:28:01,095
- How's that?
- Hey, you're very good.

544
00:28:01,263 --> 00:28:02,847
Thanks.

545
00:28:04,016 --> 00:28:06,351
What do people usually say?

546
00:28:06,977 --> 00:28:12,899
Don't ask. Like anything
from Goodogzwater to Goulashwallop.

547
00:28:13,067 --> 00:28:14,567
[GRIFFIN CHUCKLES]

548
00:28:14,735 --> 00:28:16,069
You English?

549
00:28:16,278 --> 00:28:19,280
Yeah. Well, no, no, not really.

550
00:28:19,490 --> 00:28:22,325
Well, where are you
kind of sort of not from?

551
00:28:22,534 --> 00:28:26,287
Well, do you want the long story
or the short one?

552
00:28:26,580 --> 00:28:28,664
- The long one.
- No, you'd never believe it.

553
00:28:28,874 --> 00:28:30,833
The short one's Iceland.

554
00:28:31,043 --> 00:28:32,627
Iceland.

555
00:28:32,836 --> 00:28:36,422
I didn't know anyone came from Iceland.
I thought it was just a block of ice.

556
00:28:36,590 --> 00:28:38,841
It's very green, actually.

557
00:28:39,009 --> 00:28:41,302
Really? I thought that was Greenland.

558
00:28:41,512 --> 00:28:45,807
No. Greenland's very icy.
Iceland's very green.

559
00:28:46,225 --> 00:28:49,977
They switched names to fool the Vikings,
who were trying to steal their women.

560
00:28:50,187 --> 00:28:51,229
Oh, I see.

561
00:28:51,438 --> 00:28:54,232
No. Blue sea.

562
00:28:54,441 --> 00:28:56,234
- Red sea.
- No, no, no.

563
00:28:56,568 --> 00:28:59,487
- No red.
- You're a painter.

564
00:28:59,655 --> 00:29:01,697
How did you guess?

565
00:29:03,367 --> 00:29:05,701
So, what movie did David go to see?

566
00:29:05,869 --> 00:29:09,455
Um, he went to the Rialto in Pasadena.
He always goes there.

567
00:29:09,665 --> 00:29:11,416
What's showing?

568
00:29:12,501 --> 00:29:14,836
Bicycle Thief, I think.

569
00:29:15,838 --> 00:29:18,131
It's a good movie. Have you seen it?

570
00:29:19,425 --> 00:29:21,676
No, I don't go to the movies.

571
00:29:21,844 --> 00:29:24,053
You don't? Why not?

572
00:29:26,014 --> 00:29:27,723
Oh...

573
00:29:31,145 --> 00:29:33,354
Life is too short.

574
00:29:33,647 --> 00:29:35,898
I've gotta hang up now.

575
00:29:39,445 --> 00:29:42,780
[EERIE MUSIC PLAYING
OVER THEATER SPEAKERS]

576
00:30:09,224 --> 00:30:11,809
[MAN SPEAKS IN ITALIAN ON-SCREEN]

577
00:30:19,568 --> 00:30:21,777
[SAD STRING MUSIC PLAYING
OVER THEATER SPEAKERS]

578
00:31:01,193 --> 00:31:03,027
David Kahane.

579
00:31:03,195 --> 00:31:05,446
No, you have the wrong guy, man.

580
00:31:22,506 --> 00:31:25,132
MAN 1: You didn't like it?
MAN 2: It's a foreign film.

581
00:31:26,802 --> 00:31:30,346
David Kahane. Griffin Mill.

582
00:31:31,181 --> 00:31:34,725
Griffin Mill. Yeah?

583
00:31:34,935 --> 00:31:37,103
Great movie, huh?

584
00:31:37,271 --> 00:31:41,232
It's so refreshing to see something
like this after all these cop movies...

585
00:31:41,441 --> 00:31:45,278
...and, you know, things we do.

586
00:31:45,779 --> 00:31:47,238
Maybe we'll do a remake of this.

587
00:31:47,447 --> 00:31:50,741
- You'd probably give it a happy ending.
- Oh, no, no. We'd keep it pure.

588
00:31:50,951 --> 00:31:52,827
Sure, right.

589
00:31:52,995 --> 00:31:54,662
Do you wanna write it?

590
00:31:55,539 --> 00:31:57,707
- Don't fuck with me.
- I'm not fucking with you.

591
00:31:57,916 --> 00:32:01,586
- I said that I'd get back to you, didn't I?
- Yeah. About six months ago.

592
00:32:01,753 --> 00:32:03,921
- I thought you'd forgotten.
- You were angry.

593
00:32:05,966 --> 00:32:08,551
- Maybe.
- Do you wanna talk about it?

594
00:32:09,595 --> 00:32:12,096
- Okay, sure.
- Great.

595
00:32:12,848 --> 00:32:15,433
Let's let the studio buy us a drink.

596
00:32:15,601 --> 00:32:17,643
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

597
00:32:17,811 --> 00:32:21,689
Well, if you don't mind a place where you
don't have any suck with the maître d'...

598
00:32:21,898 --> 00:32:24,984
...I know a bar down the street.
- Let's go.

599
00:32:28,488 --> 00:32:30,865
[MAN SINGING IN JAPANESE]

600
00:32:31,950 --> 00:32:34,368
KAHANE:
Have you ever been to Japan?

601
00:32:34,578 --> 00:32:38,831
GRIFFIN: Yes, I was there once
on a location scout with Steven Spielberg.

602
00:32:38,999 --> 00:32:41,167
KAHANE:
I lived there for a year.

603
00:32:41,627 --> 00:32:43,461
- Student year abroad.
- Great.

604
00:32:43,670 --> 00:32:46,422
You know, I wish I'd done that.

605
00:32:46,632 --> 00:32:49,884
Well, I think about it a lot.
I'll never forget it.

606
00:32:50,052 --> 00:32:52,011
You should write about it.

607
00:32:52,554 --> 00:32:55,556
I did. Don't you remember?

608
00:32:56,391 --> 00:32:57,850
What?

609
00:32:58,894 --> 00:32:59,935
[SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

610
00:33:00,103 --> 00:33:04,899
My idea about the American
student who goes to Japan.

611
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:08,402
That was my pitch, the one you
were supposed to get back to me on.

612
00:33:08,612 --> 00:33:09,695
You don't remember, do you?

613
00:33:09,863 --> 00:33:10,905
[APPLAUSE]

614
00:33:11,073 --> 00:33:12,948
Of course I remember.

615
00:33:14,117 --> 00:33:15,326
You never got back to me.

616
00:33:16,495 --> 00:33:18,120
Listen.

617
00:33:18,664 --> 00:33:22,166
I was an asshole, all right?

618
00:33:22,376 --> 00:33:23,834
It comes with the job.

619
00:33:24,211 --> 00:33:26,629
I'm sorry, I really am.

620
00:33:28,256 --> 00:33:30,508
I know how angry you must've been.

621
00:33:30,717 --> 00:33:33,177
I'll make it up to you.
That's what I'm here for.

622
00:33:33,887 --> 00:33:36,263
I wanna give you a deal, David.

623
00:33:36,848 --> 00:33:41,143
I'm not gonna guarantee I'm gonna make
the movie, but I am gonna give you a shot.

624
00:33:41,311 --> 00:33:43,646
[SINGING LYRICS ON MONITOR]

625
00:33:43,814 --> 00:33:48,776
Let's just, um, stop all the postcard shit,
all right?

626
00:33:49,486 --> 00:33:52,071
I'm here to say that I would like...

627
00:33:52,239 --> 00:33:54,281
...to start over.

628
00:33:55,826 --> 00:33:56,867
Friends.

629
00:33:57,035 --> 00:33:58,911
SINGER:
Let's begin again

630
00:33:59,079 --> 00:34:03,833
- Fuck you, Mill. You're a liar.
- You're stepping over the line, David.

631
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:06,127
You didn't come here
to see The Bicycle Thief.

632
00:34:06,837 --> 00:34:09,296
You came in five minutes
before the picture ended.

633
00:34:09,506 --> 00:34:11,841
You nearly tripped over my feet.

634
00:34:13,593 --> 00:34:17,012
What'd you do, call my house? Huh?

635
00:34:17,389 --> 00:34:18,973
Did you speak to the ice queen?

636
00:34:20,767 --> 00:34:23,978
You'd like her, Mill. She's a lot like you.

637
00:34:24,604 --> 00:34:26,480
All heart.

638
00:34:27,691 --> 00:34:31,485
SINGER:
Before love had really taken hold

639
00:34:31,653 --> 00:34:33,946
You're on my list, pal.

640
00:34:34,281 --> 00:34:35,740
Nothing's gonna change that.

641
00:34:39,786 --> 00:34:41,328
See you in the next reel, asshole.

642
00:34:41,496 --> 00:34:43,289
Let's start over from the start

643
00:34:43,999 --> 00:34:46,500
SINGER:
Let's forget the time

644
00:34:46,668 --> 00:34:49,295
That you nearly broke my heart

645
00:34:49,504 --> 00:34:54,091
Go everywhere we've been again

646
00:34:54,468 --> 00:34:58,804
Let's begin again

647
00:35:16,281 --> 00:35:18,407
KAHANE [SINGING]:
Let's begin again

648
00:35:19,659 --> 00:35:22,453
Let's start over from the start

649
00:35:24,122 --> 00:35:26,081
[KAHANE HUMS]

650
00:35:29,252 --> 00:35:31,003
[CAR ALARM BEEPS]

651
00:35:31,171 --> 00:35:34,423
KAHANE: That's a nice boat
you got there, movie exec.

652
00:35:35,091 --> 00:35:38,219
It's me, the writer.
You still wanna buy my story?

653
00:35:38,386 --> 00:35:41,055
I told you I'd give you a deal.
Stop by the studio in the morning.

654
00:35:41,264 --> 00:35:44,683
- We'll work something out.
- And who will I ask for?

655
00:35:45,101 --> 00:35:47,019
Larry Levy?

656
00:35:48,772 --> 00:35:50,606
What's Larry Levy got to do with this?

657
00:35:51,399 --> 00:35:53,859
- How you know about Levy?
- Don't you read the trades?

658
00:35:54,027 --> 00:35:57,071
New York Times business section?
He's moving in, you're moving out.

659
00:35:57,239 --> 00:35:59,240
You can't make a deal,
that's what they say.

660
00:35:59,407 --> 00:36:02,910
- Yesterday's news.
- Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

661
00:36:03,370 --> 00:36:05,996
Can I borrow your mobile phone? Huh?

662
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:09,416
Hi. Larry Levy.
Yeah, Larry, David Kahane here.

663
00:36:09,626 --> 00:36:12,169
Listen, Larry,
guess who's making promises...

664
00:36:12,379 --> 00:36:16,257
...about getting pictures made
to writers in parking lots.

665
00:36:16,758 --> 00:36:19,343
Guess what dumb,
son-of-a-bitch executive...

666
00:36:19,553 --> 00:36:23,305
...is trying to take advantage of me.

667
00:36:23,515 --> 00:36:27,184
I mean, do you realize
how unstoppable this guy is?

668
00:36:27,394 --> 00:36:31,230
You know, I cannot wait
to tell the world...

669
00:36:31,439 --> 00:36:34,859
...that when Griffin Mill
can't cut the pressure at work...

670
00:36:35,318 --> 00:36:37,903
...he drives out to Pasadena...

671
00:36:38,071 --> 00:36:40,990
...to pick fights with writers!

672
00:36:42,409 --> 00:36:44,159
You tell Larry Levy to give me a call.

673
00:36:44,327 --> 00:36:47,413
The word is out that he's gonna
start making meaningful pictures...

674
00:36:47,581 --> 00:36:49,498
...at the studio for a change.

675
00:36:49,708 --> 00:36:52,751
Let's... Let's forget this.
Just stop all the postcard shit.

676
00:36:52,919 --> 00:36:54,753
- I don't write postcards!
- Let's forget this!

677
00:36:54,921 --> 00:36:56,797
- I write scripts!
- We're both wrong! Okay?

678
00:36:56,965 --> 00:36:59,633
No, you're wrong, buddy.
You're in over your head.

679
00:36:59,801 --> 00:37:03,637
That's why you're losing your job.
And then what are you gonna do?

680
00:37:03,805 --> 00:37:07,141
Huh? I can write. What can you do?

681
00:37:11,813 --> 00:37:14,064
I said, let's forget this.

682
00:37:19,070 --> 00:37:21,113
Ah, shit.

683
00:37:23,199 --> 00:37:26,827
Mill, you okay? Are you all right?

684
00:37:26,995 --> 00:37:28,203
[GRIFFIN YELLS]

685
00:37:33,919 --> 00:37:39,089
Keep it to yourself!

686
00:37:39,633 --> 00:37:42,092
Keep it to yourself.

687
00:37:42,844 --> 00:37:44,511
[GURGLING]

688
00:38:05,116 --> 00:38:06,951
Kahane?

689
00:39:05,010 --> 00:39:06,885
[DOG BARKING NEARBY]

690
00:39:27,198 --> 00:39:28,699
LEVY:
You know what's interesting?

691
00:39:28,908 --> 00:39:30,868
I mean, who's writing this new ending?

692
00:39:31,036 --> 00:39:33,120
Who wrote the new ending
of Fatal Attraction?

693
00:39:33,288 --> 00:39:34,705
- The audience.
BONNIE: In that case...

694
00:39:34,873 --> 00:39:37,583
LEVY: A million-plus screenwriters,
the audience wrote that ending.

695
00:39:37,751 --> 00:39:40,961
BONNIE: Who's to say what it would have
done if you left the original ending?

696
00:39:41,171 --> 00:39:42,588
- You can't say.
LEVY: You're right.

697
00:39:42,756 --> 00:39:45,340
But you can say that
it's done 300 million worldwide...

698
00:39:45,508 --> 00:39:47,968
...with the ending selected
from the test screening.

699
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:51,889
Larry, I don't believe that
you've met my assistant, Whitney Gersh.

700
00:39:52,098 --> 00:39:54,600
- No, I haven't.
- It's a great pleasure to meet you.

701
00:39:54,768 --> 00:39:56,643
[EXECS CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

702
00:39:56,811 --> 00:39:58,771
REG: What are you doing?
LEVY: How's your picture?

703
00:39:58,938 --> 00:40:01,065
- It just tested last week.
BONNIE: Doing well.

704
00:40:01,232 --> 00:40:03,067
LEVY: How well?
BONNIE: It was our first test.

705
00:40:03,276 --> 00:40:04,818
Excuse me, Walter.

706
00:40:04,986 --> 00:40:09,364
Um, Joel, Griffin still isn't in, but I really
think we have to start this meeting.

707
00:40:09,532 --> 00:40:12,117
Okay, Celia. Thank you.

708
00:40:14,412 --> 00:40:16,538
WALTER:
You remember a movie called D.O.A.?

709
00:40:16,748 --> 00:40:18,999
Sure I do.
Eddie O'Brien and Pam Britton.

710
00:40:19,167 --> 00:40:22,336
Disney did a remake in '87 or '88.

711
00:40:22,587 --> 00:40:25,339
Yeah, well, I think we got, uh,
pretty much the same situation.

712
00:40:25,507 --> 00:40:28,008
Keep our noses clean, Walter.

713
00:40:31,262 --> 00:40:33,931
LEVY: It's a shame to waste the picture.
It's a great picture.

714
00:40:34,099 --> 00:40:36,183
EXEC: It's a great story.
- Who said we're wasting it?

715
00:40:36,351 --> 00:40:39,520
- Where did that come from?
LEVY: You know what's interesting?

716
00:40:39,687 --> 00:40:43,190
- We're all too busy to go see movies...
JAN: Griffin, you're really late.

717
00:40:43,358 --> 00:40:45,484
- They're waiting inside.
LEVY: You ought to try it.

718
00:40:45,652 --> 00:40:48,570
GRIFFIN: What's this?
JAN: It's a script from Todd Smith.

719
00:40:49,614 --> 00:40:52,533
LEVY: We need to give them
the kind of pictures they want...

720
00:40:52,700 --> 00:40:54,868
...not the kind these writers
wanna give them.

721
00:40:55,078 --> 00:40:58,330
I know you guys
spend a lot of time with writers.

722
00:40:58,498 --> 00:41:02,167
- Believe me, you have my deepest sympathy.
GRIFFIN: Excuse me.

723
00:41:02,377 --> 00:41:06,130
- Hello. Sorry I'm late.
CELIA: You certainly are.

724
00:41:06,798 --> 00:41:09,216
WALTER: Jan, can I talk to you, please?
JAN: Yeah.

725
00:41:09,467 --> 00:41:11,718
WALTER: Just a couple minutes
in your office is fine.

726
00:41:12,595 --> 00:41:17,474
LEVISON: Griffin, you missed the formal
welcoming ceremony. You know Larry Levy.

727
00:41:18,101 --> 00:41:20,185
Of course. Hi, Larry.

728
00:41:21,855 --> 00:41:23,730
- Hi.
- Larry was able to get out of Fox...

729
00:41:23,982 --> 00:41:27,192
...earlier than he thought
and has come aboard as of this morning.

730
00:41:27,360 --> 00:41:30,529
GRIFFIN:
Great. Well, let's, uh... Let's start.

731
00:41:31,030 --> 00:41:33,448
- Larry was in the middle of something.
- No. I wasn't.

732
00:41:33,616 --> 00:41:35,868
I was just killing time waiting for Griffin.

733
00:41:36,077 --> 00:41:39,037
Well, no. Finish. What were you saying?

734
00:41:39,247 --> 00:41:41,748
I was just saying that
I've yet to meet a writer...

735
00:41:41,958 --> 00:41:46,253
...who could change water into wine, and
we have a tendency to treat them like that.

736
00:41:46,588 --> 00:41:48,839
CELIA: As soon as you're finished.
- Not at this studio.

737
00:41:49,591 --> 00:41:52,342
Million, million and a half
for these scripts. It's...

738
00:41:52,510 --> 00:41:53,594
It's nuts.

739
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:56,054
And I think avoidable.

740
00:41:56,973 --> 00:42:00,058
When was the last time you actually
bought a ticket to see a movie?

741
00:42:00,226 --> 00:42:03,103
- Actually paid your own money to see it?
- Last night.

742
00:42:04,105 --> 00:42:06,064
Pasadena. The Bicycle Thief.

743
00:42:06,232 --> 00:42:09,610
- You went to see The Bicycle Thief?
- I love that film. It's a great film.

744
00:42:09,777 --> 00:42:13,280
LEVY: It's art movie. Doesn't count.
We're talking about "movie" movies.

745
00:42:13,448 --> 00:42:14,489
Jesus, people.

746
00:42:14,657 --> 00:42:17,659
All I'm saying is I think
a lot of time and money can be saved...

747
00:42:17,827 --> 00:42:20,078
...if we came up with these stories
on our own.

748
00:42:20,246 --> 00:42:21,955
Where are these stories coming from?

749
00:42:22,123 --> 00:42:24,583
Anywhere, anywhere.
It doesn't matter. Anywhere. Um...

750
00:42:24,792 --> 00:42:27,628
The newspaper. Pick a story. Any story.

751
00:42:27,795 --> 00:42:29,087
[STEVE CLEARS THROAT]

752
00:42:29,255 --> 00:42:30,714
All right.

753
00:42:31,007 --> 00:42:34,134
"Immigrants Protest Budget Cuts
in Literacy Program."

754
00:42:34,302 --> 00:42:37,763
Human spirit overcoming adversity.
Horatio Alger in the barrio.

755
00:42:37,931 --> 00:42:40,641
Put Jimmy Smits in it
and you got a sexy Stand and Deliver.

756
00:42:40,808 --> 00:42:44,102
- Next. Come on.
- Larry, this isn't my field.

757
00:42:44,312 --> 00:42:47,356
LEVY: Marty, it doesn't matter.
Just give it a shot. You can't lose here.

758
00:42:47,523 --> 00:42:49,483
MARTY:
Okay.

759
00:42:49,943 --> 00:42:53,987
How about, uh,
"Mudslide Kills 60 in Slums of Chili"?

760
00:42:54,239 --> 00:42:57,783
LEVY: That's good. Triumph over tragedy.
Sounds like a John Boorman picture.

761
00:42:57,992 --> 00:43:00,869
You slap a happy ending on it,
the script will write itself.

762
00:43:01,120 --> 00:43:04,957
- Bon. Here, give me the paper.
BONNIE: Gee, I don't know, Lar.

763
00:43:05,166 --> 00:43:06,750
Give it a shot.

764
00:43:06,960 --> 00:43:08,418
[BONNIE SIGHS]

765
00:43:08,586 --> 00:43:11,880
BONNIE: "Further Bond Losses
Push Dow Down 7. 15."

766
00:43:12,340 --> 00:43:14,925
LEVY: Okay.
BONNIE: I see Connery as Bond.

767
00:43:15,093 --> 00:43:17,719
LEVY: Funny. A good thing Oliver Stone
wasn't listening to you.

768
00:43:17,887 --> 00:43:20,347
- Where would we have been?
BONNIE: We would have been spared...

769
00:43:20,515 --> 00:43:22,307
...having to sit through Wall Street.

770
00:43:22,475 --> 00:43:24,518
LEVY:
Marty, what did Wall Street do worldwide?

771
00:43:24,686 --> 00:43:27,229
MARTY:
Seventy, 75, maybe 80.

772
00:43:27,397 --> 00:43:30,649
LEVY: Eighty million dollars,
a couple of Oscars. Nothing to sneeze at.

773
00:43:30,817 --> 00:43:34,027
Okay. I think Larry's point is well taken.
Let's move on now.

774
00:43:34,195 --> 00:43:37,948
Griffin, uh, can you give us an update
on the Taylor Hackford project?

775
00:43:38,366 --> 00:43:39,950
Griffin?

776
00:43:40,368 --> 00:43:41,827
Yeah.

777
00:43:43,079 --> 00:43:46,915
I was just thinking what an interesting
concept it is to eliminate the writer...

778
00:43:47,125 --> 00:43:50,460
...from the artistic process.

779
00:43:51,045 --> 00:43:55,424
If we can just get rid of these actors and
directors, maybe we got something here.

780
00:43:55,633 --> 00:43:57,217
[ALL CHUCKLE]

781
00:44:01,389 --> 00:44:02,848
GRIFFIN:
Hello, Walter.

782
00:44:03,474 --> 00:44:06,226
- Make yourself at home.
WALTER: Mr. Mill.

783
00:44:06,394 --> 00:44:09,062
I understand you were kind of late
coming in this morning.

784
00:44:09,397 --> 00:44:12,733
- You all right?
- I'm fine.

785
00:44:12,942 --> 00:44:15,235
Appreciate your concern.

786
00:44:16,571 --> 00:44:18,864
What can I do for you, Walter?

787
00:44:19,073 --> 00:44:22,242
Don't tell me you came here
to pitch me a story.

788
00:44:22,410 --> 00:44:25,037
Ha, ha.
That's exactly what I've come to do.

789
00:44:25,204 --> 00:44:30,250
It's a good one too. It's about a writer.
Sort of. David Kahane.

790
00:44:32,754 --> 00:44:33,795
David Kahane.

791
00:44:34,005 --> 00:44:36,798
- Who's David Kahane?
- Oh, you met him.

792
00:44:37,383 --> 00:44:38,759
Well, I meet a lot of writers.

793
00:44:39,218 --> 00:44:42,179
Uh-huh. But this particular writer
that you met was murdered last night...

794
00:44:42,347 --> 00:44:46,016
...in back of the Rialto Theater in Pasadena.
- Murdered?

795
00:44:46,476 --> 00:44:50,103
Well, come to think of it,
Pasadena's as good a place to die as any.

796
00:44:51,898 --> 00:44:53,440
So, what's the story?

797
00:44:53,649 --> 00:44:55,609
Twenty-five words or less?

798
00:44:55,818 --> 00:44:58,945
Okay. Movie exec calls writer.

799
00:44:59,113 --> 00:45:02,824
Writer's girlfriend says he's at the movies.
Exec got to the movies, meets writer...

800
00:45:02,992 --> 00:45:07,412
...drinks with writer. Writer gets conked
and dies in 4 inches of dirty water.

801
00:45:07,622 --> 00:45:09,956
Movie exec is in deep shit.

802
00:45:11,125 --> 00:45:12,834
What do you think?

803
00:45:13,169 --> 00:45:16,129
That's more than 25 words
and it's bullshit.

804
00:45:16,297 --> 00:45:17,339
[WALTER CHUCKLES]

805
00:45:17,507 --> 00:45:20,634
Pasadena Homicide doesn't think
it's bullshit. They got a complete report.

806
00:45:21,469 --> 00:45:24,721
You met Kahane at the Rialto.
You got drunk with him at a restaurant.

807
00:45:24,889 --> 00:45:28,141
He left before you did.
That's the last time anyone saw him alive...

808
00:45:28,309 --> 00:45:30,143
...except you maybe.

809
00:45:30,436 --> 00:45:32,521
Why are you denying this?

810
00:45:33,356 --> 00:45:36,733
Well, what do the police think?

811
00:45:36,984 --> 00:45:40,987
They think it's a botched robbery.
You know...

812
00:45:41,322 --> 00:45:42,823
...window of his car was busted.

813
00:45:43,032 --> 00:45:46,159
He surprised someone
trying to take the radio.

814
00:45:46,369 --> 00:45:48,703
There was a fight, he was killed.

815
00:45:48,871 --> 00:45:50,997
I didn't kill him, Walter...

816
00:45:51,874 --> 00:45:53,834
...but I went to see him.

817
00:45:54,710 --> 00:45:56,336
I know I said I didn't, but I did.

818
00:45:57,004 --> 00:46:00,090
- Why'd you lie to me?
- Well...

819
00:46:00,341 --> 00:46:02,551
...now's not a very good time for me.

820
00:46:02,760 --> 00:46:06,096
Haven't you heard the rumors?
I'm on my way out.

821
00:46:06,347 --> 00:46:09,182
Just what I need,
a little more controversy.

822
00:46:09,350 --> 00:46:10,976
Just not a good time, Walter.

823
00:46:12,353 --> 00:46:13,979
Look.

824
00:46:14,730 --> 00:46:18,191
I am in charge of studio security
in every definition of the word...

825
00:46:18,359 --> 00:46:21,736
...which means it is my job
to take care of a studio executive...

826
00:46:21,988 --> 00:46:25,657
...should he be, uh, shall we say,
under suspicion of murder...

827
00:46:25,825 --> 00:46:29,703
...at a time when profits are down and
the company is vulnerable for a takeover.

828
00:46:29,912 --> 00:46:32,998
It is my job to keep this
very, very, very, very quiet!

829
00:46:34,375 --> 00:46:36,084
You wanna help?

830
00:46:36,586 --> 00:46:39,379
- Of course.
- Then stop lying.

831
00:46:40,214 --> 00:46:43,049
- How many meetings did you have?
- One.

832
00:46:43,259 --> 00:46:45,886
- Not counting last night?
- Not counting last night.

833
00:46:46,053 --> 00:46:48,221
Why'd you go all the way
to Pasadena to meet?

834
00:46:48,389 --> 00:46:51,224
He had an idea I was interested in.
I wanted to talk to him.

835
00:46:51,392 --> 00:46:52,559
His girlfriend.

836
00:46:52,768 --> 00:46:55,896
I guess she was a friend of yours too.
Think fast!

837
00:46:56,063 --> 00:46:58,732
Jesus Christ, Walter,
what do you think? What is this?

838
00:46:58,941 --> 00:47:02,027
The third degree. If you don't like it,
wait till the police start asking.

839
00:47:02,195 --> 00:47:04,154
- I'll go right now.
- They'll be a lot less polite!

840
00:47:04,322 --> 00:47:07,949
- You come with me!
- You're acting like someone's who's guilty.

841
00:47:08,284 --> 00:47:09,910
You're not guilty, are you?

842
00:47:10,244 --> 00:47:12,245
For the last time, I'm not a murderer.

843
00:47:12,455 --> 00:47:14,498
[FAX MACHINE BEEPS]

844
00:47:29,597 --> 00:47:31,348
WALTER:
Bad news?

845
00:47:32,099 --> 00:47:35,685
- What?
- The fax. Is it bad news?

846
00:47:35,937 --> 00:47:37,062
No.

847
00:47:38,648 --> 00:47:40,065
Business as usual.

848
00:47:41,651 --> 00:47:45,153
PHIL: The Hollywood system
did not murder David Kahane.

849
00:47:45,571 --> 00:47:48,615
Not the $98-million movie,
not the $12-million actor.

850
00:47:48,783 --> 00:47:54,287
Not even the million-dollar deal
that David Kahane never landed.

851
00:47:54,455 --> 00:48:00,710
No, the most that we can pin on Hollywood
is assault with intent to kill.

852
00:48:01,212 --> 00:48:06,091
Because society is responsible
for this particular murder...

853
00:48:06,300 --> 00:48:11,888
...and it is to society that we must look
if we are to have any justice for that crime.

854
00:48:12,056 --> 00:48:14,349
Because someone in the night...

855
00:48:14,892 --> 00:48:19,813
...killed David Kahane, and that person
will have to bear the guilt.

856
00:48:21,023 --> 00:48:26,903
And if David were here right now,
I know in my heart that he would say:

857
00:48:27,613 --> 00:48:30,156
"Cut the shit, Phil.

858
00:48:30,408 --> 00:48:34,369
What did you learn from all of this?
Did you learn anything from this?"

859
00:48:34,620 --> 00:48:37,581
And I'd say,
"Uh, yeah, David, uh, I've learned a lot.

860
00:48:37,748 --> 00:48:40,667
We here, uh... We'll take it from here."

861
00:48:41,043 --> 00:48:44,838
And the next time we sell a script
for a million dollars...

862
00:48:45,131 --> 00:48:48,508
...the next time we nail some
shit-bag producer to the wall, we'll say:

863
00:48:48,676 --> 00:48:51,011
"That's another one for David Kahane."

864
00:48:54,640 --> 00:48:58,935
David was working on something the day
he died. I'd, uh, like to share it with you.

865
00:48:59,854 --> 00:49:02,856
"Blackness. A mangy dog barks.

866
00:49:03,649 --> 00:49:08,653
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the street hunt for food.

867
00:49:08,863 --> 00:49:11,281
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock
goes off.

868
00:49:11,657 --> 00:49:14,784
Interior. Flophouse room. Early morning.

869
00:49:15,036 --> 00:49:18,038
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

870
00:49:18,247 --> 00:49:21,750
Light streams in through holes
in the yellowing window shades.

871
00:49:21,959 --> 00:49:24,544
Moths dance in the beams of light.

872
00:49:24,754 --> 00:49:27,881
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

873
00:49:28,049 --> 00:49:30,925
Stop on an old shoe.

874
00:49:31,177 --> 00:49:32,802
It's empty."

875
00:49:37,433 --> 00:49:39,225
That's as far as he got.

876
00:49:40,436 --> 00:49:42,729
That's the last thing he wrote.

877
00:49:43,814 --> 00:49:45,607
So long, Dave.

878
00:49:46,275 --> 00:49:47,942
Fade out.

879
00:49:48,653 --> 00:49:49,903
Thank you.

880
00:50:06,128 --> 00:50:09,422
Who are you? You're not a writer.

881
00:50:10,341 --> 00:50:12,592
No. I'm Griffin Mill.

882
00:50:12,802 --> 00:50:17,430
- We spoke the night David was...
- Blue sea, white sea. Yes.

883
00:50:17,640 --> 00:50:19,182
It turned out you were right.

884
00:50:19,350 --> 00:50:22,143
- What?
- It was a red sea.

885
00:50:22,728 --> 00:50:25,105
Oh. Yeah.

886
00:50:26,732 --> 00:50:29,359
You're the only person I know here.

887
00:50:29,944 --> 00:50:32,654
Listen, I'm really sorry about David.

888
00:50:32,947 --> 00:50:34,739
He was, uh...

889
00:50:35,157 --> 00:50:36,908
...a talent.

890
00:50:37,243 --> 00:50:39,285
You really think so?

891
00:50:39,620 --> 00:50:42,330
I always suspected he was...

892
00:50:42,790 --> 00:50:46,042
...uniquely untalented.

893
00:50:46,919 --> 00:50:48,294
It's nice of you to say that.

894
00:50:48,462 --> 00:50:51,756
- Nice of you to come. You didn't have to.
GRIFFIN: Well, I did.

895
00:50:52,133 --> 00:50:55,802
You know, I was probably
the last person to see him alive.

896
00:50:55,970 --> 00:50:58,346
Yeah. The police told me.

897
00:50:58,806 --> 00:51:02,392
- Well, not quite the last, surely.
- No.

898
00:51:04,019 --> 00:51:06,980
I'm sure this is a terrible time for you.

899
00:51:07,314 --> 00:51:09,357
Is there anything you need or?

900
00:51:09,567 --> 00:51:11,776
No, really. I...

901
00:51:11,944 --> 00:51:14,195
I don't feel bad.

902
00:51:14,405 --> 00:51:17,157
It's like when my parents died.

903
00:51:17,324 --> 00:51:21,578
I didn't feel anything at all.
They were just gone.

904
00:51:22,580 --> 00:51:25,707
Well, I'm sure it hasn't sunk in yet.

905
00:51:25,916 --> 00:51:29,169
- That was years ago.
- No, I meant David.

906
00:51:29,336 --> 00:51:30,587
Oh.

907
00:51:30,755 --> 00:51:32,213
Oh, God.

908
00:51:32,423 --> 00:51:35,425
These people. I don't like it here.

909
00:51:35,676 --> 00:51:41,848
They're all expecting me to grieve
and mourn, and I can't talk to them.

910
00:51:43,350 --> 00:51:45,518
David's gone...

911
00:51:45,853 --> 00:51:48,188
...and I'm somewhere else already.

912
00:51:48,522 --> 00:51:51,316
- Will you take me home?
- What?

913
00:51:51,484 --> 00:51:53,443
Will you take me home?

914
00:51:54,236 --> 00:51:57,238
Sure. I'm right here.

915
00:52:34,109 --> 00:52:36,402
These are very interesting. I like them.

916
00:52:36,570 --> 00:52:40,240
- Would you like a drink?
- No, thanks.

917
00:52:40,574 --> 00:52:42,617
- Where do you show?
- Hmm?

918
00:52:42,785 --> 00:52:43,910
Gallery. What gallery?

919
00:52:44,078 --> 00:52:46,746
- Who's your dealer?
- I don't have a dealer.

920
00:52:46,956 --> 00:52:49,290
I couldn't sell these.
They're never finished.

921
00:52:49,458 --> 00:52:51,084
Bicky?

922
00:52:51,669 --> 00:52:54,379
No, thanks. They're never finished?

923
00:52:54,588 --> 00:52:58,883
No, they're just what I do, for myself.

924
00:52:59,093 --> 00:53:00,927
What I feel.

925
00:53:02,137 --> 00:53:04,430
You ask lots of questions, Mr. Mill.

926
00:53:04,932 --> 00:53:08,935
You're just like the police.
That's all they did, ask questions.

927
00:53:10,104 --> 00:53:11,771
They asked me a lot about you.

928
00:53:11,939 --> 00:53:13,731
- Did they?
- Mm-hm.

929
00:53:13,899 --> 00:53:17,569
How long we've known each other,
if you'd ever been to the house before.

930
00:53:17,736 --> 00:53:20,655
Well, I suppose they have to ask
those questions.

931
00:53:20,948 --> 00:53:22,615
I don't see why.

932
00:53:22,950 --> 00:53:25,285
Because that's what police do.

933
00:53:25,995 --> 00:53:28,705
- Can I ask you a question?
- Sure.

934
00:53:29,290 --> 00:53:31,666
Why was it so important
to see David that night?

935
00:53:31,917 --> 00:53:33,793
What was so urgent?

936
00:53:35,921 --> 00:53:38,548
Well, he pitched me a story
a few months ago and...

937
00:53:38,799 --> 00:53:40,925
- The Japan story, right?
- Yes, the Japan story.

938
00:53:41,135 --> 00:53:44,804
I liked it at the time, but it needed work,
especially the ending.

939
00:53:44,972 --> 00:53:47,473
And I was sitting in my office that day...

940
00:53:47,641 --> 00:53:50,518
...and it suddenly occurred to me
how to make the ending work.

941
00:53:50,728 --> 00:53:52,812
So, what was it?

942
00:53:53,147 --> 00:53:56,649
- What?
- Your idea for the ending?

943
00:53:57,484 --> 00:53:58,985
Up.

944
00:53:59,695 --> 00:54:01,195
- "Up"?
- Up.

945
00:54:01,447 --> 00:54:04,365
- What does that mean?
- As opposed to down. Moods.

946
00:54:04,658 --> 00:54:07,827
You know, happy as opposed to sad,
hopeful as opposed to depressing.

947
00:54:08,746 --> 00:54:11,664
- What did you think of his ending?
- I never read it.

948
00:54:13,500 --> 00:54:16,169
- You never read it?
- Nope.

949
00:54:16,378 --> 00:54:18,379
I don't like reading.

950
00:54:18,672 --> 00:54:21,758
- Do you like books?
- I like words...

951
00:54:22,009 --> 00:54:23,676
...and letters...

952
00:54:23,886 --> 00:54:26,262
...but I'm not crazy
about complete sentences.

953
00:54:26,889 --> 00:54:28,014
Hmm.

954
00:54:28,182 --> 00:54:29,891
So, what did he think?

955
00:54:30,851 --> 00:54:34,395
He walked out on me, actually.
I don't think David liked me very much.

956
00:54:34,897 --> 00:54:39,108
I think he just didn't like happy endings.

957
00:54:42,404 --> 00:54:44,364
Put your face here.

958
00:54:45,741 --> 00:54:47,533
Great.

959
00:54:49,370 --> 00:54:51,913
What are you doing?
You're not gonna paint me, are you?

960
00:54:52,081 --> 00:54:55,249
I might put you in one of my paintings.

961
00:54:55,542 --> 00:54:58,878
There's one that I want to do
of an Icelandic hero.

962
00:54:59,088 --> 00:55:02,131
He's a thief and he's made of fire.

963
00:55:02,383 --> 00:55:04,717
- Hmm, but you might not like that.
- Why not?

964
00:55:05,511 --> 00:55:08,471
Because you're in the movies...

965
00:55:08,639 --> 00:55:11,557
...and in the movies, you can't
have thieves as heroes, can you?

966
00:55:12,101 --> 00:55:15,687
I don't know about that. We have
a long tradition of gangsters in the movies.

967
00:55:15,854 --> 00:55:19,065
Oh, yes, but they always have to
suffer for their crimes, don't they?

968
00:55:20,567 --> 00:55:22,735
We should pay for our crimes,
shouldn't we?

969
00:55:22,945 --> 00:55:27,532
I don't know. Knowing that you've
committed a crime is suffering enough.

970
00:55:27,741 --> 00:55:32,578
If you don't suffer,
maybe it wasn't a crime after all.

971
00:55:33,080 --> 00:55:35,581
Anyway, what difference does it make?

972
00:55:35,791 --> 00:55:38,918
It has nothing to do
with how things really are.

973
00:55:43,257 --> 00:55:44,799
You don't really believe that, do you?

974
00:55:44,967 --> 00:55:46,009
[JUNE CHUCKLES]

975
00:55:46,176 --> 00:55:49,095
I don't know what I believe, Mr. Mill.

976
00:55:49,430 --> 00:55:52,265
That is just what I feel.

977
00:55:53,976 --> 00:55:57,603
You know what you are,
June whatever-your-name-is?

978
00:55:58,105 --> 00:55:59,564
You're a pragmatic anarchist.

979
00:56:00,816 --> 00:56:02,859
- Is that what I am?
- That's what you are.

980
00:56:03,110 --> 00:56:05,111
I never was sure.

981
00:56:09,783 --> 00:56:13,202
AVERY:
Could I just pick this up? Yeah?

982
00:56:13,370 --> 00:56:15,997
- Ooh, it's heavy.
WALTER: Thirty-seven ounces.

983
00:56:16,206 --> 00:56:18,374
Really? Oh, look, look.

984
00:56:18,625 --> 00:56:20,960
I wanna thank my mother,
and her mother...

985
00:56:21,170 --> 00:56:23,463
...and her father's mother,
who was the...

986
00:56:23,630 --> 00:56:24,672
[GRIFFIN AND AVERY CHUCKLE]

987
00:56:24,840 --> 00:56:27,341
- Hello.
- Hello. Ha, ha.

988
00:56:27,634 --> 00:56:29,093
Meet Detective Susan Avery.

989
00:56:29,303 --> 00:56:30,344
- How do you do?
- Hello.

990
00:56:30,596 --> 00:56:31,971
- My partner.
- Willa Broom.

991
00:56:32,181 --> 00:56:34,140
My pleasure. Let's go in here.

992
00:56:34,308 --> 00:56:37,226
This is the first real movie studio
Detective Avery's been to.

993
00:56:37,394 --> 00:56:40,146
GRIFFIN: Oh, really?
AVERY: Well, aside from the Universal tour.

994
00:56:40,355 --> 00:56:42,899
When my family comes in,
I always take them out there.

995
00:56:43,150 --> 00:56:46,486
Been out there so often,
I kind of feel like I'm ready to direct.

996
00:56:46,653 --> 00:56:48,821
WALTER: You'll probably do better
than the film grads...

997
00:56:49,031 --> 00:56:51,157
...they're handing the cameras
out to nowadays.

998
00:56:51,325 --> 00:56:53,993
I'm sorry I didn't call you
when I heard Kahane was dead.

999
00:56:54,161 --> 00:56:55,536
- Heard or read?
- Read.

1000
00:56:55,746 --> 00:56:57,163
Why didn't you?

1001
00:56:57,331 --> 00:57:00,708
Walter asked me the same question.
I wish I had a better answer for it...

1002
00:57:00,918 --> 00:57:03,503
...but all I can say
is that I didn't think about it.

1003
00:57:03,670 --> 00:57:05,129
Hmm.

1004
00:57:05,923 --> 00:57:09,509
- How did you know where he would be?
- His wife told me...

1005
00:57:09,676 --> 00:57:12,095
...he was seeing The Bicycle Thief.
- Girlfriend.

1006
00:57:12,513 --> 00:57:13,846
Girlfriend.

1007
00:57:14,056 --> 00:57:15,973
Girlfriend. I didn't know either of them.

1008
00:57:16,141 --> 00:57:18,643
I was feeling restless.
I thought I'd go see the movie.

1009
00:57:18,811 --> 00:57:22,021
If he was there, I was gonna
talk to him about a job he was good for.

1010
00:57:22,189 --> 00:57:24,315
AVERY: So you got to the theater,
you saw him and...?

1011
00:57:24,525 --> 00:57:27,443
GRIFFIN: We went and had a drink
at a Japanese place he knew about.

1012
00:57:27,611 --> 00:57:30,738
It was a wild, incredible scene.
It was like Tokyo.

1013
00:57:30,948 --> 00:57:33,866
But he left before you did.
Why didn't you leave together?

1014
00:57:34,076 --> 00:57:36,661
It was an incredible scene.
I was having a great time.

1015
00:57:36,870 --> 00:57:38,538
Then why didn't you stay longer?

1016
00:57:38,747 --> 00:57:42,875
Well, the people stopped singing and
then it was just a bar, and I don't drink.

1017
00:57:43,043 --> 00:57:45,878
- You drank with him.
- Well, when in Rome...

1018
00:57:46,547 --> 00:57:48,422
- Did you know him socially?
- No.

1019
00:57:48,590 --> 00:57:49,882
- Been to his house?
- No.

1020
00:57:50,092 --> 00:57:52,760
- Know anything about him personally?
- No.

1021
00:57:52,970 --> 00:57:56,806
Griffin. Guess we're gonna
let you get back to work now.

1022
00:57:59,434 --> 00:58:03,062
- Something's bothering you. What is it?
- Well, I...

1023
00:58:03,272 --> 00:58:08,234
I just have to ask you, did you see him
in the parking lot after you left?

1024
00:58:08,443 --> 00:58:10,236
No. I parked on the street.

1025
00:58:10,404 --> 00:58:13,573
I drive a Range Rover
so I always feel safer when it's visible.

1026
00:58:13,782 --> 00:58:15,992
Out on the street,
who's gonna smash a window?

1027
00:58:16,160 --> 00:58:17,201
Hmm.

1028
00:58:17,369 --> 00:58:20,705
If you had a shitty car, you would
have been parked in the parking lot?

1029
00:58:20,914 --> 00:58:23,666
If I had a shitty car,
I might be a dead man.

1030
00:58:24,334 --> 00:58:26,836
Somehow, I think
you're a little too lucky for that.

1031
00:58:27,087 --> 00:58:28,713
Thank you.

1032
00:58:28,922 --> 00:58:30,173
ASSISTANT: Okay.
TOMLIN: Come on.

1033
00:58:30,340 --> 00:58:32,758
ASSISTANT: Sixty-three, Take 3, mark.
TOMLIN: Wait one second.

1034
00:58:32,926 --> 00:58:34,260
DIRECTOR:
Now.

1035
00:58:35,345 --> 00:58:36,762
Action.

1036
00:58:36,930 --> 00:58:38,139
[GLENN CLEARS THROAT]

1037
00:58:38,307 --> 00:58:40,766
No, goddamn it, Peterson,
you listen to me.

1038
00:58:40,976 --> 00:58:44,103
I been around a while. I got a nose.
This situation stinks.

1039
00:58:44,313 --> 00:58:46,355
It stinks of The Company.

1040
00:58:46,607 --> 00:58:48,441
That's right, Peterson, the fucking CIA.

1041
00:58:48,609 --> 00:58:50,443
- You ever heard of it?
LEVY: Lily understands.

1042
00:58:50,611 --> 00:58:52,737
It's the kind of operation
those whiz-kid fucks...

1043
00:58:52,946 --> 00:58:54,780
You don't understand
what he's going for.

1044
00:58:54,948 --> 00:58:56,616
- I guess I don't.
- I find it hard...

1045
00:58:56,783 --> 00:58:58,868
...to listen to you
when you don't understand.

1046
00:58:59,119 --> 00:59:01,662
- Would you shut up, please? Could you?
- Oh, kiss my ass.

1047
00:59:01,830 --> 00:59:03,289
LEVY:
You can't even see anything.

1048
00:59:03,457 --> 00:59:05,791
I have to cut because
my robe caught on the drawer.

1049
00:59:06,001 --> 00:59:08,252
DIRECTOR: Oh, for chrissakes.
TOMLIN: I couldn't help it.

1050
00:59:08,420 --> 00:59:10,671
EXEC 1: I like this guy. He's great.
EXEC 2: Scotty Glenn?

1051
00:59:10,839 --> 00:59:13,716
- What kind of water is that?
EXEC 1: A cowboy, an FBI, priest, lover.

1052
00:59:13,884 --> 00:59:15,134
Can I have some Volvic, please?

1053
00:59:15,344 --> 00:59:18,471
DIRECTOR: Action.
- No, goddamn...

1054
00:59:18,639 --> 00:59:21,682
LEVISON: I heard the police
came to see you about this dead writer.

1055
00:59:21,850 --> 00:59:23,351
Who was this guy?

1056
00:59:23,560 --> 00:59:25,478
GRIFFIN:
His name was David Kahane.

1057
00:59:25,687 --> 00:59:28,481
I never heard of him.
Did we ever hire him for anything?

1058
00:59:28,649 --> 00:59:30,942
I was thinking about it.

1059
00:59:31,610 --> 00:59:34,320
He pitched me a story.
I went out to talk to him about it.

1060
00:59:34,488 --> 00:59:36,447
TOMLIN: I don't have to endure your mouth.
- Jesus.

1061
00:59:36,698 --> 00:59:40,910
Poor bastard. His ship is about to come in,
some black kid wants his money for crack.

1062
00:59:41,078 --> 00:59:43,204
I'm sorry.
I don't wanna criticize you, babe...

1063
00:59:43,372 --> 00:59:45,665
...but I'm supposed to
be having a conversation.

1064
00:59:45,874 --> 00:59:48,834
TOMLIN: Are you talking to me?
- Are the cops still bothering you?

1065
00:59:49,044 --> 00:59:51,587
DIRECTOR: Action.
GRIFFIN: No. No, I don't think so.

1066
00:59:51,838 --> 00:59:55,341
LEVISON: Let Stuckel handle it. He'll
give them a couple passes to a screening...

1067
00:59:55,509 --> 00:59:59,220
...where they can sit two rows behind
Michelle Pfeiffer. They'll leave you alone.

1068
00:59:59,554 --> 01:00:01,055
- Griffin?
- Yes.

1069
01:00:01,223 --> 01:00:06,227
Um, a guy named Joe Gillis called
and he said he wants you to meet him...

1070
01:00:06,395 --> 01:00:09,563
...at the St. James Club
around 10:00 on the patio.

1071
01:00:09,856 --> 01:00:11,607
- Know who this is?
- Never heard of him.

1072
01:00:11,858 --> 01:00:15,361
- He said you'd know him.
- Anybody know who Joe Gillis is?

1073
01:00:15,529 --> 01:00:18,322
LEVISON: He's the character William Holden
played in Sunset Boulevard.

1074
01:00:18,490 --> 01:00:20,449
The writer who gets killed
by the movie star.

1075
01:00:20,617 --> 01:00:22,868
BONNIE: Gloria Swanson.
CELIA: That is a fantastic movie.

1076
01:00:23,036 --> 01:00:25,663
GLENN: All I know is we're doing this
my way. I happen to think...

1077
01:00:25,831 --> 01:00:26,956
[GRIFFIN CHUCKLES]

1078
01:00:27,124 --> 01:00:31,043
Oh, that guy. Last week he said
he was Charles Foster Kane.

1079
01:00:31,628 --> 01:00:33,713
Week before that it was Rhett Butler.

1080
01:00:33,922 --> 01:00:36,716
Why would they think that
I'd kill my own sister's husband?

1081
01:00:36,883 --> 01:00:38,884
LEVY:
You wanna compare grosses, Bonnie?

1082
01:00:39,052 --> 01:00:41,178
I was in love with him.

1083
01:00:41,346 --> 01:00:43,306
[SIREN WAILING]

1084
01:01:22,179 --> 01:01:23,471
Griffin?

1085
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:25,014
- Griffin.
- Malcolm McDowell.

1086
01:01:25,182 --> 01:01:26,932
- Hi. How are you?
- Hi. Good to see you.

1087
01:01:27,100 --> 01:01:30,478
Listen, the next time
you wanna badmouth me...

1088
01:01:30,687 --> 01:01:33,105
...have the courage to do it to my face.

1089
01:01:33,315 --> 01:01:35,608
You guys are all the same.

1090
01:01:45,619 --> 01:01:48,037
CIVELLA: You love it there?
- I love it. It's just wonderful.

1091
01:01:48,205 --> 01:01:50,664
You love your career too,
don't you? What is it, Tom?

1092
01:01:50,916 --> 01:01:54,293
A complete disaster. Look at what
happened in Heaven's Gate with Cimino.

1093
01:01:54,461 --> 01:01:56,962
- It just ended.
- We both are concerned about your ca...

1094
01:01:57,130 --> 01:01:58,964
I knew an actor,
won't mention his name.

1095
01:01:59,132 --> 01:02:01,759
MacDOWELL: Where I live, I know
how people think and how they feel.

1096
01:02:01,927 --> 01:02:03,803
- But it's Montana.
- Montana will end you.

1097
01:02:03,970 --> 01:02:06,639
- It ended Cimino on Heaven's Gate.
- Excuse me.

1098
01:02:06,890 --> 01:02:08,182
Griffin Mill.

1099
01:02:08,392 --> 01:02:10,726
- Hi. Andy Civella.
- Andy. How are you?

1100
01:02:10,977 --> 01:02:14,480
Hey, I've got Andie MacDowell sitting
over here. You know her? She's so hot.

1101
01:02:14,648 --> 01:02:16,816
- Come over, meet her.
- Still living in New York?

1102
01:02:16,983 --> 01:02:19,568
Well, I couldn't live here.
I'm allergic to happiness. Ha, ha.

1103
01:02:19,778 --> 01:02:21,237
- Andie, Griffin Mill.
- Hi, Andie.

1104
01:02:21,405 --> 01:02:22,863
- How are you?
- She's my namesake.

1105
01:02:23,031 --> 01:02:25,074
- How are the kids?
CIVELLA: She's the smart Andie...

1106
01:02:25,242 --> 01:02:27,827
...and I'm the pretty one.
- He's wonderful. Thank you.

1107
01:02:27,994 --> 01:02:29,870
You geniuses know each other.
Tom Oakley.

1108
01:02:30,038 --> 01:02:32,665
- Of course we do. Hi. How are you?
- Oh, yes. Hi, Tom.

1109
01:02:33,250 --> 01:02:35,751
Funny. I just ran into
Malcolm McDowell in the lobby.

1110
01:02:35,919 --> 01:02:37,503
- Oh, really?
- Roddy McDowall...

1111
01:02:37,671 --> 01:02:39,839
...is related to a cousin
of my brother-in-law.

1112
01:02:40,006 --> 01:02:42,591
Well, I'm not related
to either one of them.

1113
01:02:42,759 --> 01:02:44,468
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1114
01:02:52,936 --> 01:02:54,437
If I write it, I direct it.

1115
01:02:54,646 --> 01:02:57,022
The last three pictures you directed
were bombs.

1116
01:02:57,190 --> 01:02:58,274
- One broke even.
- Bombs!

1117
01:02:58,442 --> 01:03:00,526
- Thank you for the drink.
- Worst of the bunch.

1118
01:03:00,735 --> 01:03:02,695
- I really have to go.
- You gotta go, Andie?

1119
01:03:02,863 --> 01:03:05,030
- Come on, let's go.
- We'll walk you to the car.

1120
01:03:05,198 --> 01:03:07,741
- No, it's okay. Don't worry about it.
- Hang on. Griffin.

1121
01:03:07,909 --> 01:03:09,535
Griffin, we'd like to buy you a drink.

1122
01:03:09,703 --> 01:03:11,370
- I am sorry. I can't.
- Have a drink.

1123
01:03:11,538 --> 01:03:14,039
- I'm meeting someone. Business.
- Should've told him...

1124
01:03:14,207 --> 01:03:16,750
...about Habeas Corpus.
- Of course, but he's busy.

1125
01:03:16,960 --> 01:03:19,712
- Is there anyone waiting for me?
- No one's asked.

1126
01:03:19,921 --> 01:03:23,674
Well, I'm expecting someone.
I'll, uh, be out by the pool.

1127
01:03:24,050 --> 01:03:26,594
But he'll get back to us, right, Griffin?

1128
01:03:26,761 --> 01:03:28,637
- Griffin.
- Andie?

1129
01:03:28,805 --> 01:03:30,389
[CIVELLA WHISTLES]

1130
01:03:42,903 --> 01:03:44,737
[SIREN WAILING]

1131
01:03:44,905 --> 01:03:46,739
[HELICOPTER SOARING ABOVE]

1132
01:04:02,547 --> 01:04:05,216
CIVELLA: Oh, sorry. Sorry, Griffin. Ha, ha.
- Jesus, Andy, it's you.

1133
01:04:05,425 --> 01:04:08,135
- Of course it's me.
- Listen, I can't ask you to join me.

1134
01:04:08,345 --> 01:04:11,555
- I told you, I'm meeting somebody.
- Yeah, you're meeting me.

1135
01:04:11,723 --> 01:04:14,600
- We got some big business.
- You? You?

1136
01:04:14,768 --> 01:04:17,478
- Why not me?
- Jesus, Andy, you think this is funny?

1137
01:04:17,646 --> 01:04:20,314
- Think this is fucking funny?
- What are you talking about?

1138
01:04:20,524 --> 01:04:22,149
Wouldn't she make a great Nora?

1139
01:04:22,359 --> 01:04:25,110
God, I'd love to write
another Doll's House for her.

1140
01:04:25,278 --> 01:04:27,905
Oh, did you meet Tom Oakley?

1141
01:04:28,156 --> 01:04:29,448
Yes.

1142
01:04:29,658 --> 01:04:32,284
- You mean, you didn't call me?
- No, I didn't call you.

1143
01:04:32,827 --> 01:04:35,829
I'm sorry. I'm really sorry.

1144
01:04:36,289 --> 01:04:39,583
Listen. I really am meeting somebody.

1145
01:04:39,793 --> 01:04:41,961
There's no way I can hear a pitch
right now.

1146
01:04:42,128 --> 01:04:44,588
- You'll have to call me tomorrow.
- No, I can't do it tomorrow.

1147
01:04:44,756 --> 01:04:45,798
[PAGER BEEPS]

1148
01:04:45,966 --> 01:04:47,216
I've got a meeting at Paramount.

1149
01:04:47,384 --> 01:04:49,677
- I've got a meeting at Universal.
- Congratulations.

1150
01:04:49,844 --> 01:04:51,720
If you don't hear it now,
you'll lose it.

1151
01:04:51,888 --> 01:04:53,889
- Then I lose it, all right?
- It'll take 20 seconds.

1152
01:04:54,057 --> 01:04:56,392
- When your friend gets here...
- What friend? Who?

1153
01:04:56,560 --> 01:04:58,018
Whoever you're gonna meet here.

1154
01:05:00,772 --> 01:05:02,398
Twenty-five words or less.

1155
01:05:02,607 --> 01:05:06,235
Absolutely. Tom, you...
No, you sit here, Tom. Go.

1156
01:05:07,153 --> 01:05:09,154
OAKLEY: District attorney's
at a moral crossroads...

1157
01:05:09,322 --> 01:05:11,824
CIVELLA: Tom. Jesus Christ!
OAKLEY: Okay. Okay, okay. Uh...

1158
01:05:12,200 --> 01:05:15,035
We open outside the largest
penitentiary in California.

1159
01:05:15,245 --> 01:05:18,622
It's night, it's raining.
A limousine comes in through the gate...

1160
01:05:18,832 --> 01:05:22,001
...past a tight knot of demonstrators
holding a candlelight vigil.

1161
01:05:22,210 --> 01:05:26,005
The candles under the umbrellas
make them glow like Japanese lanterns.

1162
01:05:26,673 --> 01:05:29,008
That's nice. I haven't seen that before.
Good.

1163
01:05:29,175 --> 01:05:32,761
A lone demonstrator, a black woman,
steps in front of the limousine.

1164
01:05:32,971 --> 01:05:35,222
The lights illuminate her like a spirit.

1165
01:05:35,432 --> 01:05:39,643
Her eyes fix upon
those of the sole passenger.

1166
01:05:41,104 --> 01:05:43,022
The moment is devastating
between them.

1167
01:05:43,231 --> 01:05:46,358
He's the DA, she's the mother
of the person that's being executed.

1168
01:05:46,526 --> 01:05:48,986
You're good. See, I told you. He's good.

1169
01:05:49,195 --> 01:05:50,446
GRIFFIN: Go on.
OAKLEY: Okay.

1170
01:05:50,655 --> 01:05:53,032
The DA believes in the death penalty.

1171
01:05:53,241 --> 01:05:57,703
And the execution is a hard case.
Black, 19 and definitely guilty.

1172
01:05:57,871 --> 01:05:59,705
We're in the greatest democracy
in the world...

1173
01:05:59,914 --> 01:06:02,541
...and 36 percent of the people
on death row are black.

1174
01:06:02,751 --> 01:06:04,585
- Poor, disadvantaged black.
- More. More.

1175
01:06:04,794 --> 01:06:07,463
And he swears that
the next person he sees to die...

1176
01:06:07,672 --> 01:06:10,049
...is gonna be smart, rich and white.

1177
01:06:10,216 --> 01:06:12,718
- You, me, whoever.
- What a hook, huh?

1178
01:06:12,927 --> 01:06:16,055
- Beauty hook. Cut to the chase, Tom.
- Okay. Okay, okay.

1179
01:06:16,222 --> 01:06:20,559
Cut from the DA to
an upmarket suburban neighborhood.

1180
01:06:20,769 --> 01:06:22,186
A couple have a fight.

1181
01:06:22,395 --> 01:06:26,106
He leaves in a fit, gets in a car.
It's the same rainy night.

1182
01:06:26,316 --> 01:06:28,984
The car spins out on a road,
goes into a ravine.

1183
01:06:29,486 --> 01:06:31,070
The body is swept away.

1184
01:06:31,237 --> 01:06:33,781
Now, when the police examine the car...

1185
01:06:33,990 --> 01:06:36,325
...they find the brakes
have been tampered with.

1186
01:06:36,534 --> 01:06:39,787
It's murder and the DA
decides to go for the big one.

1187
01:06:40,288 --> 01:06:42,414
He's gonna put the wife
in the gas chamber.

1188
01:06:42,624 --> 01:06:44,458
But the DA falls in love with the wife.

1189
01:06:44,626 --> 01:06:47,920
Of course he falls in love, but he
puts her in the gas chamber anyway.

1190
01:06:48,129 --> 01:06:50,839
Then he finds out the husband is alive...

1191
01:06:51,049 --> 01:06:53,258
...that he faked his death.

1192
01:06:53,760 --> 01:06:57,054
The DA breaks into the prison,
runs down death row...

1193
01:06:57,263 --> 01:06:58,972
...but he gets there too late.

1194
01:06:59,182 --> 01:07:01,517
The gas pellets have been dropped.

1195
01:07:01,851 --> 01:07:03,519
She's dead.

1196
01:07:03,978 --> 01:07:05,646
I'll tell you...

1197
01:07:06,022 --> 01:07:08,107
...there's not a dry eye in the house.

1198
01:07:08,650 --> 01:07:10,901
- She's dead?
OAKLEY: She's dead.

1199
01:07:11,111 --> 01:07:14,613
She's dead.
Because that's the reality.

1200
01:07:14,823 --> 01:07:17,282
The innocent die.

1201
01:07:18,326 --> 01:07:20,953
- Who's the DA?
- Ah. No one.

1202
01:07:21,162 --> 01:07:23,414
- No one?
- "No stars on this project."

1203
01:07:23,581 --> 01:07:28,001
- We're going out on a limb on this one.
- You know, like unknown stage actors...

1204
01:07:28,169 --> 01:07:30,129
...or maybe somebody English
like what's-his-name.

1205
01:07:30,296 --> 01:07:31,588
OAKLEY:
Mm-hm.

1206
01:07:32,924 --> 01:07:34,842
- Why?
OAKLEY: Why? Why?

1207
01:07:35,051 --> 01:07:37,845
Because this story
is just too damned important...

1208
01:07:38,012 --> 01:07:40,013
...to risk being overwhelmed
by personality.

1209
01:07:40,223 --> 01:07:42,933
Yeah, that's fine for action pictures,
but this is special.

1210
01:07:43,101 --> 01:07:44,768
We want real people here.

1211
01:07:44,978 --> 01:07:47,813
We don't want people coming in
with any preconceived notions.

1212
01:07:48,022 --> 01:07:51,567
- We want them to see a district attorney.
- Bruce Willis.

1213
01:07:51,776 --> 01:07:54,445
No. Not Bruce Willis, not Kevin Costner.

1214
01:07:54,654 --> 01:07:57,489
This is an innocent woman
fighting for her life.

1215
01:07:57,657 --> 01:07:59,366
- Julia Roberts.
GRIFFIN: If we can get her.

1216
01:07:59,576 --> 01:08:02,077
CIVELLA: Of course we can get her.
- If I'm perfectly honest...

1217
01:08:02,245 --> 01:08:05,539
...if I think about this,
this isn't even an American film.

1218
01:08:07,792 --> 01:08:11,044
- It's not?
OAKLEY: No, no. There are no stars.

1219
01:08:11,254 --> 01:08:12,796
No pat happy endings.

1220
01:08:12,964 --> 01:08:16,759
No Schwarzenegger, no stickups,
no terrorists.

1221
01:08:16,968 --> 01:08:20,679
This is a tough story. A tragedy
in which an innocent woman dies.

1222
01:08:20,847 --> 01:08:24,725
Why? Because that happens.

1223
01:08:24,893 --> 01:08:26,643
[PAGER BEEPS]

1224
01:08:27,020 --> 01:08:29,021
Habeas Corpus.

1225
01:08:29,230 --> 01:08:32,065
That's what we're calling it.
"Produce the corpse."

1226
01:08:32,275 --> 01:08:33,776
What do you say? Yes or no?

1227
01:08:34,944 --> 01:08:36,695
That pitch was more than 25 words.

1228
01:08:36,905 --> 01:08:39,782
Yeah, but it's brilliant.
What's the verdict, Griffin?

1229
01:08:39,991 --> 01:08:41,992
WAITER:
Mr. Mill, for you.

1230
01:08:42,619 --> 01:08:45,412
GRIFFIN: Who gave this to you?
WAITER: I received it at the front desk.

1231
01:08:45,622 --> 01:08:47,247
OAKLEY:
What is it?

1232
01:08:50,502 --> 01:08:52,002
It's, um...

1233
01:08:52,170 --> 01:08:55,339
It's from the person I was meeting.
He's not coming.

1234
01:08:55,507 --> 01:08:57,758
Well, do we have a shot? Griffin.

1235
01:08:57,967 --> 01:09:00,469
It's an intriguing idea.
Give me a call at the studio.

1236
01:09:00,637 --> 01:09:01,970
CIVELLA: Yeah!
- There's a scene...

1237
01:09:02,138 --> 01:09:04,223
...in Throne of Blood
that has exactly the texture.

1238
01:09:04,390 --> 01:09:06,892
- Tom. Just say "thank you."
- If you wanna... Okay.

1239
01:09:07,060 --> 01:09:08,477
She has to die. No Hollywood ending.

1240
01:09:08,645 --> 01:09:10,437
- Tom, "thank you," say.
- God!

1241
01:09:10,605 --> 01:09:11,647
[PAGER BEEPS]

1242
01:09:40,844 --> 01:09:42,553
[CAR PHONE RINGS]

1243
01:10:20,842 --> 01:10:21,884
[RATTLING]

1244
01:10:29,183 --> 01:10:31,268
[TIRES SQUEAL AND HORNS HONKING]

1245
01:10:43,197 --> 01:10:45,073
[HORN HONKS]

1246
01:11:05,845 --> 01:11:08,805
Fuck you! You fucking dog-shit writer!

1247
01:11:09,015 --> 01:11:10,432
You fucking try to kill me!

1248
01:11:11,768 --> 01:11:12,809
Fuck.

1249
01:11:32,872 --> 01:11:34,039
[JUNE GASPS]

1250
01:11:34,207 --> 01:11:37,501
Oh, God. You gave me such a scare.

1251
01:11:37,710 --> 01:11:39,544
What are you doing here?

1252
01:11:39,712 --> 01:11:40,754
[CHUCKLES]

1253
01:11:40,922 --> 01:11:44,132
You gave me such a fright. Come in.

1254
01:11:44,634 --> 01:11:46,218
Come on in.

1255
01:11:47,929 --> 01:11:51,765
What's the matter? You look terrible.

1256
01:11:52,183 --> 01:11:53,475
What's up?

1257
01:11:56,104 --> 01:11:58,230
Sit down. I'll get you a drink.

1258
01:12:09,450 --> 01:12:11,368
Something happened?

1259
01:12:12,704 --> 01:12:14,037
Is it too late? I...

1260
01:12:14,247 --> 01:12:15,247
- No, no, no.
- Sorry.

1261
01:12:15,415 --> 01:12:16,957
It's not too late. No.

1262
01:12:17,166 --> 01:12:20,919
- I don't even know what time it is.
- What's wrong?

1263
01:12:26,426 --> 01:12:28,260
What are you painting? Is that me?

1264
01:12:28,428 --> 01:12:31,346
Yep. It's you.

1265
01:12:33,016 --> 01:12:34,349
See?

1266
01:12:34,559 --> 01:12:36,810
GRIFFIN:
Do you have snakes in Iceland?

1267
01:12:36,978 --> 01:12:38,770
Snakes? No, I don't think so, no.

1268
01:12:39,022 --> 01:12:40,647
Are you afraid of snakes?

1269
01:12:40,815 --> 01:12:43,650
I don't know.
I've never come close to a real one.

1270
01:12:43,860 --> 01:12:46,028
They scare the shit out of me.

1271
01:12:52,160 --> 01:12:55,746
- Here, have another.
- I don't usually drink.

1272
01:12:59,542 --> 01:13:02,085
Something happened tonight.

1273
01:13:02,670 --> 01:13:04,838
Yes, but, uh...

1274
01:13:06,758 --> 01:13:09,426
...there's something else
I have to tell you.

1275
01:13:11,929 --> 01:13:14,097
This isn't easy for me.

1276
01:13:15,475 --> 01:13:16,558
Yes?

1277
01:13:23,399 --> 01:13:26,068
How about if I just
get on with my work...

1278
01:13:26,694 --> 01:13:30,614
...and you talk to me
when you feel like, okay?

1279
01:13:37,288 --> 01:13:39,956
I came very close to dying tonight.

1280
01:13:43,669 --> 01:13:45,295
All I could think about was you.

1281
01:13:45,463 --> 01:13:46,755
[JUNE SIGHS]

1282
01:13:46,923 --> 01:13:49,132
I don't even know you.

1283
01:13:49,842 --> 01:13:52,219
But you came into my mind...

1284
01:13:54,555 --> 01:13:58,850
...and I couldn't...
I couldn't think of anything else.

1285
01:14:01,938 --> 01:14:04,689
Remember that first night
we spoke on the phone?

1286
01:14:07,026 --> 01:14:09,236
I was outside these windows...

1287
01:14:10,530 --> 01:14:12,823
...watching you and, um...

1288
01:14:15,660 --> 01:14:18,370
It was so exciting and so...

1289
01:14:19,872 --> 01:14:21,957
...new and...

1290
01:14:23,960 --> 01:14:26,044
...strange.

1291
01:14:28,965 --> 01:14:31,716
I can't get you out of my mind.

1292
01:14:34,804 --> 01:14:37,472
Are you making love to me?

1293
01:14:40,017 --> 01:14:42,394
Yes, I guess I am.

1294
01:14:43,896 --> 01:14:45,772
I guess I am.

1295
01:14:49,235 --> 01:14:58,243
I wanna make love to you.

1296
01:14:59,287 --> 01:15:01,246
It's too soon.

1297
01:15:04,542 --> 01:15:06,793
It's too soon, isn't it?

1298
01:15:08,754 --> 01:15:11,339
It's so strange how things happen.

1299
01:15:13,342 --> 01:15:15,427
David was here...

1300
01:15:15,720 --> 01:15:17,679
...then he left.

1301
01:15:18,806 --> 01:15:20,807
You arrived.

1302
01:15:23,186 --> 01:15:25,979
Maybe it's just the timing,
but I feel like...

1303
01:15:26,147 --> 01:15:29,733
...I would go anywhere with you...

1304
01:15:31,027 --> 01:15:32,944
...if you asked.

1305
01:15:36,699 --> 01:15:38,950
But we mustn't hurry things.

1306
01:15:39,118 --> 01:15:45,081
You know, we can't hurry things
any more than we can stop them.

1307
01:15:47,293 --> 01:15:49,586
I think you better go now.

1308
01:15:49,921 --> 01:15:52,339
I think I'm going to cry now.

1309
01:15:56,802 --> 01:15:59,346
Better go, quick.

1310
01:16:05,561 --> 01:16:06,937
I'm sorry.

1311
01:16:07,146 --> 01:16:10,482
No, no, no, don't be sorry.
Just go home...

1312
01:16:11,108 --> 01:16:13,235
...and get some sleep...

1313
01:16:13,945 --> 01:16:15,570
...and call me.

1314
01:16:16,489 --> 01:16:18,156
Tomorrow.

1315
01:16:19,450 --> 01:16:21,910
Invite me on a proper date.

1316
01:16:22,995 --> 01:16:24,871
I'd like that.

1317
01:16:39,887 --> 01:16:41,388
GRIFFIN [OVER INTERCOM]:
Jan?

1318
01:16:41,681 --> 01:16:42,681
- Jan!
JAN: Yeah?

1319
01:16:42,848 --> 01:16:44,307
GRIFFIN:
Get Larry Levy on the phone.

1320
01:16:44,475 --> 01:16:47,269
JAN: I don't think he's on the lot.
GRIFFIN: Try his car.

1321
01:16:48,020 --> 01:16:49,145
Isn't he at Fox?

1322
01:16:49,355 --> 01:16:51,356
He used to be. Not anymore.

1323
01:16:51,524 --> 01:16:54,818
I pitched him something a few months ago
and he hated it.

1324
01:16:55,319 --> 01:16:57,445
LEVY [OVER SPEAKER]: Yeah, Griffin.
- Yeah, yeah.

1325
01:16:57,613 --> 01:16:59,072
Listen, I've got Tom Oakley...

1326
01:16:59,240 --> 01:17:02,033
...and Andy Civella.
I wouldn't be bothering you if I didn't...

1327
01:17:02,285 --> 01:17:04,202
...think they had an idea
you should hear.

1328
01:17:04,370 --> 01:17:06,788
- Hi, guys.
CIVELLA: Hi, Larry.

1329
01:17:06,998 --> 01:17:09,791
Uh, the next voice you're gonna hear
has got an English accent.

1330
01:17:10,001 --> 01:17:11,835
Tom Oakley. I'm Andy Civella.

1331
01:17:12,044 --> 01:17:14,504
Hi, Andy. I know Tom.
How are you, Tom?

1332
01:17:14,672 --> 01:17:16,673
Uh, very well, Larry. And yourself?

1333
01:17:17,049 --> 01:17:18,842
Fine. What's your story?

1334
01:17:19,927 --> 01:17:22,637
We open outside San Quentin. It's night.

1335
01:17:22,805 --> 01:17:24,055
[MIMICS RAIN]

1336
01:17:24,223 --> 01:17:27,183
It's raining.
A limousine enters through the front gate...

1337
01:17:27,351 --> 01:17:31,521
...past a tight knot of demonstrators holding
a candlelight vigil. The candles are...

1338
01:17:31,731 --> 01:17:34,899
...flickering underneath the umbrellas,
glowing like Japanese lanterns.

1339
01:17:35,401 --> 01:17:38,695
A lone demonstrator, black woman,
steps in front of the limousine.

1340
01:17:38,904 --> 01:17:41,239
Her eyes connect
with the lone passenger.

1341
01:17:41,449 --> 01:17:45,910
It's a devastating moment
for both of them. Incredibly potent.

1342
01:17:47,913 --> 01:17:51,416
No stars, no Schwarzenegger,
no pat Hollywood endings...

1343
01:17:51,584 --> 01:17:54,711
...no car chases.
This is an American tragedy...

1344
01:17:54,920 --> 01:17:56,880
...in which an innocent woman dies.

1345
01:17:57,089 --> 01:18:00,759
Because that happens. That's reality.

1346
01:18:01,802 --> 01:18:04,095
LEVY [OVER SPEAKER]:
Take me off the speakerphone, Griffin.

1347
01:18:05,389 --> 01:18:06,514
Yeah?

1348
01:18:06,724 --> 01:18:11,227
I don't know. It's a really hot story,
but what is this bullshit, no stars?

1349
01:18:11,437 --> 01:18:15,273
Let me give you a little tip, Larry.
Levison came to power on two movies.

1350
01:18:15,441 --> 01:18:17,734
They made $300 million
and had no stars in them.

1351
01:18:17,902 --> 01:18:20,362
He's gonna love this idea.
It'll remind him of his youth.

1352
01:18:20,529 --> 01:18:23,573
You know what his motto used to be?
No stars, just talent.

1353
01:18:23,783 --> 01:18:27,494
- Has anyone else heard this?
GRIFFIN: I don't think so. No.

1354
01:18:28,245 --> 01:18:29,579
We should make a deal now.

1355
01:18:29,955 --> 01:18:32,707
Tomorrow may be too late.
Can we get ahold of Levison?

1356
01:18:32,917 --> 01:18:35,293
Yeah, I'll get Levison.
Uh, when can you be back?

1357
01:18:35,503 --> 01:18:38,004
- I'll be there right after my AA meeting.
- Oh, Larry.

1358
01:18:38,172 --> 01:18:40,548
I didn't realize you, uh,
had a drinking problem.

1359
01:18:40,716 --> 01:18:41,925
LEVY:
Well...

1360
01:18:42,134 --> 01:18:46,638
...I don't really, but that's where all the
deals are being made these days. See you.

1361
01:18:48,516 --> 01:18:51,768
Tom, that was a hell of a pitch.

