for me. Um, Willa. Excuse me.

1587
01:31:12,884 --> 01:31:15,719
Did you happen to see where the tampons
went that were in here?

1588
01:31:15,887 --> 01:31:18,848
- Because I can't seem to find them.
- I didn't take them.

1589
01:31:19,057 --> 01:31:20,349
Who took them? Did he?

1590
01:31:20,559 --> 01:31:22,351
- I don't know. I didn't.
- Who did?

1591
01:31:22,561 --> 01:31:25,396
- I didn't take them.
- You see this? Damn.

1592
01:31:26,731 --> 01:31:29,233
Um, so do you have a break in the case?

1593
01:31:29,442 --> 01:31:31,235
Oh, what makes you say that?

1594
01:31:31,403 --> 01:31:34,238
Well, why else
would you bring me here?

1595
01:31:35,490 --> 01:31:36,615
Why else, indeed.

1596
01:31:36,783 --> 01:31:37,825
[CHUCKLES]

1597
01:31:37,993 --> 01:31:43,414
Paul. Paul, why have you brought Mr. Mill
in here today?

1598
01:31:43,582 --> 01:31:46,083
- To look at some pictures.
AVERY: Willa.

1599
01:31:46,585 --> 01:31:48,127
Pictures?

1600
01:31:48,378 --> 01:31:53,007
Listen, could you...? If you remember,
what were you, uh, wearing that night?

1601
01:31:53,258 --> 01:31:57,094
I was wearing a double-breasted suit,
I believe.

1602
01:31:57,929 --> 01:31:59,763
Oh, it's all right. What's the matter?

1603
01:31:59,931 --> 01:32:02,433
- Mr. Mill, you're so jumpy. Sit down.
- I'll get it.

1604
01:32:02,601 --> 01:32:06,145
No, no, she... That's what she's here for.
It's all right. Have a seat.

1605
01:32:06,396 --> 01:32:08,022
GRIFFIN: Sorry.
AVERY: No problem.

1606
01:32:08,690 --> 01:32:10,107
Okay.

1607
01:32:10,275 --> 01:32:12,276
Will you take a look at this gentle...?

1608
01:32:12,485 --> 01:32:13,986
- Where were they?
BROOM: Right here.

1609
01:32:14,196 --> 01:32:16,697
She found them, look.
You're right. Ha, ha.

1610
01:32:16,948 --> 01:32:19,658
Oh, wait a minute. No, no.
These aren't mine.

1611
01:32:19,826 --> 01:32:21,869
These are slender regular.
These are yours.

1612
01:32:22,037 --> 01:32:23,454
BROOM:
Yeah, I guess you have jumbo.

1613
01:32:23,622 --> 01:32:24,622
[FLY BUZZING]

1614
01:32:24,789 --> 01:32:26,665
AVERY:
Well, I do use jumbo. These are not mine.

1615
01:32:27,042 --> 01:32:29,710
God. Just trying to help you out.

1616
01:32:29,878 --> 01:32:33,505
Um, look, did you see this guy
the night of the murder?

1617
01:32:35,800 --> 01:32:38,219
Sorry, ha, ha. Um...

1618
01:32:38,386 --> 01:32:41,972
No. Uh, you're putting me
in a terrible position here.

1619
01:32:42,140 --> 01:32:44,016
I would hate to get
the wrong person arrested.

1620
01:32:44,184 --> 01:32:47,436
Oh, please. This is Pasadena.
We do not arrest the wrong person.

1621
01:32:47,646 --> 01:32:50,773
That's L.A. See, L.A., they kick
your ass and then they arrest you.

1622
01:32:50,941 --> 01:32:53,609
That's what they do. We don't do that.
Remember last year?

1623
01:32:53,777 --> 01:32:56,153
What was that guy's name?
They put him on the tape.

1624
01:32:56,363 --> 01:32:57,655
- King.
AVERY: That's right, King.

1625
01:32:57,864 --> 01:33:00,074
DELIVERY MAN: BLT.
- He was the wrong guy.

1626
01:33:03,328 --> 01:33:06,080
- Do you have a witness?
- Now, I can't answer that.

1627
01:33:06,331 --> 01:33:10,417
Well, either you have a witness
or these are suspects in similar murders.

1628
01:33:10,585 --> 01:33:12,836
Mr. Mill, have you been going
to detective school?

1629
01:33:13,046 --> 01:33:17,424
No, actually, we're doing a movie right
now called The Lonely Room. Scott Glenn...

1630
01:33:17,592 --> 01:33:20,010
...plays a detective like you.
- Is he a black woman?

1631
01:33:20,220 --> 01:33:21,553
GRIFFIN: No.
- Don't give me turkey.

1632
01:33:21,721 --> 01:33:25,391
- Lily Tomlin's in that? I heard about that.
- Actually I was drawing a comparison...

1633
01:33:25,600 --> 01:33:28,102
...not based on race or gender.

1634
01:33:28,353 --> 01:33:33,023
Speaking of which,
did you go out with, uh, June, uh...?

1635
01:33:33,900 --> 01:33:35,109
What is that woman's name?

1636
01:33:36,403 --> 01:33:37,611
Gudmundsdottir.

1637
01:33:38,196 --> 01:33:41,949
Ha. What is it? Who? Spell it for me.

1638
01:33:42,117 --> 01:33:44,576
G-U-D-M-U-N-D-S-D-O-T-T-l-R.

1639
01:33:44,786 --> 01:33:46,370
AVERY:
Well, that really helps.

1640
01:33:46,538 --> 01:33:48,622
Could you...?
Uh, did you go out with June...?

1641
01:33:48,790 --> 01:33:50,708
GRIFFIN: Gudmundsdottir.
- Yeah. Her. Last night?

1642
01:33:50,875 --> 01:33:52,167
Yes, I did.

1643
01:33:52,335 --> 01:33:54,169
You guys known each other
a long time?

1644
01:33:54,379 --> 01:33:57,381
No, I spoke to her for the first time
the night Kahane was killed.

1645
01:33:57,549 --> 01:33:58,757
Wow.

1646
01:33:58,925 --> 01:34:00,884
- So you didn't know her before this?
- No.

1647
01:34:01,094 --> 01:34:02,720
We met over the phone.

1648
01:34:02,887 --> 01:34:04,888
We got to talking,
one thing led to another.

1649
01:34:05,098 --> 01:34:06,890
You fuck her?

1650
01:34:07,892 --> 01:34:11,729
- What kind of question is that?
- I think it's pretty direct. Did you fuck her?

1651
01:34:12,439 --> 01:34:15,357
I wouldn't answer that question
without a lawyer in the room.

1652
01:34:15,525 --> 01:34:17,901
Then I probably wouldn't
even answer that question.

1653
01:34:18,111 --> 01:34:20,529
Why don't you ask your friend?
He's been following me.

1654
01:34:20,697 --> 01:34:22,823
- He'll probably know.
- All right.

1655
01:34:23,074 --> 01:34:28,078
Paul, did Mr. Mill
fuck June Hudmuuhunta?

1656
01:34:28,288 --> 01:34:29,538
I didn't see him.

1657
01:34:29,706 --> 01:34:32,499
- Got away with it. He didn't see you.
- What are you implying?

1658
01:34:32,667 --> 01:34:35,753
I'm not implying. I asked a direct question.
Did you fuck her?

1659
01:34:35,962 --> 01:34:38,255
I told you I wouldn't answer that
without a lawyer.

1660
01:34:38,423 --> 01:34:41,258
- Why you getting hot under the collar?
- You're being rude.

1661
01:34:41,426 --> 01:34:42,593
Oh, well, excuse me.

1662
01:34:42,802 --> 01:34:46,764
But I think it's kind of soon for her
to be gallivanting in the streets with you.

1663
01:34:46,973 --> 01:34:49,224
I'm there for her as a friend, Miss Avery.

1664
01:34:49,392 --> 01:34:51,560
- Mm.
- Why don't you call her?

1665
01:34:51,770 --> 01:34:54,938
I'm sure she'll be happy to pick over
the horror of what's happened...

1666
01:34:55,106 --> 01:34:58,567
...and tell you how we became friends.

1667
01:34:58,777 --> 01:35:00,402
What is this, fucking Iran?

1668
01:35:00,570 --> 01:35:04,198
Since when does the state tell us how long,
and with whom we can share our grief?

1669
01:35:04,366 --> 01:35:05,908
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1670
01:35:06,076 --> 01:35:08,202
Or do you hold June Gudmundsdottir...

1671
01:35:08,370 --> 01:35:10,788
...to a special code of conduct
reserved for women?

1672
01:35:10,955 --> 01:35:13,457
[ALL LAUGHING]

1673
01:35:18,088 --> 01:35:20,130
What the fuck are you laughing at?

1674
01:35:20,298 --> 01:35:22,466
It's just, just...

1675
01:35:22,634 --> 01:35:24,635
- I'd like to talk to my lawyer.
AVERY: Oh, my God.

1676
01:35:24,803 --> 01:35:27,721
DeLONGPRE: "One of us. One of us."
AVERY: Can't even say the bitch's name!

1677
01:35:27,889 --> 01:35:31,600
DeLONGPRE:
"One of us. One of us. One of us."

1678
01:35:41,903 --> 01:35:44,321
WALTER: It's time for you
to get yourself a real good lawyer.

1679
01:35:44,531 --> 01:35:47,741
I had a drink with the guy, Walter.
That's all.

1680
01:35:47,992 --> 01:35:53,122
If you went to Pasadena with the intent
to kill, you could go to the gas chamber.

1681
01:35:53,832 --> 01:35:56,500
I went to Pasadena
with the intent to hire.

1682
01:35:57,252 --> 01:35:58,377
So you say.

1683
01:35:58,545 --> 01:36:01,338
JAN: Griffin, the Schecter brothers are here.
ERIC: Griffin. Griffin.

1684
01:36:01,506 --> 01:36:03,424
Griffin. Don't make us wait.

1685
01:36:03,675 --> 01:36:04,842
Who is this man?

1686
01:36:05,009 --> 01:36:06,844
ERIC:
A travel agent called. You're confirmed.

1687
01:36:07,011 --> 01:36:08,345
JAN:
He grabbed the phone from me.

1688
01:36:08,555 --> 01:36:11,765
- Travel agent?
- I'm going to Puerto Vallarta.

1689
01:36:12,350 --> 01:36:14,852
- You're leaving the country?
GRIFFIN: For the weekend.

1690
01:36:15,019 --> 01:36:16,186
It's a risk.

1691
01:36:16,521 --> 01:36:17,771
Why?

1692
01:36:18,022 --> 01:36:21,024
Because Larry Levy
could have my office in three days.

1693
01:36:21,234 --> 01:36:24,695
- That's what Walter thinks.
- You know something I don't know?

1694
01:36:27,031 --> 01:36:28,031
You're pretty smooth.

1695
01:36:28,658 --> 01:36:30,868
I sleep at night.

1696
01:36:31,953 --> 01:36:34,204
- You really should run the studio.
GRIFFIN: Tell a friend.

1697
01:36:34,414 --> 01:36:37,040
ERIC:
Yeah, Walter, it's been real.

1698
01:36:37,208 --> 01:36:39,543
Griffin. We're tired of shopping
everything around.

1699
01:36:39,711 --> 01:36:43,130
We wanna go exclusive to one studio.
How much have our three pictures made?

1700
01:36:43,298 --> 01:36:45,424
CARL: $105 million.
ERIC: I know some people do better.

1701
01:36:45,592 --> 01:36:47,217
We're consistent and under budget.

1702
01:36:47,385 --> 01:36:49,386
CARL:
He's not listening. Let's go to Columbia.

1703
01:36:49,554 --> 01:36:52,556
ERIC: We already went to Columbia.
CARL: Oh, yeah. What did they say?

1704
01:36:52,724 --> 01:36:53,807
ERIC: Bonnie.
CARL: Hey, Bon.

1705
01:36:53,975 --> 01:36:55,893
Hey. I got the Tom Wolfe book.

1706
01:36:56,603 --> 01:36:58,228
Congratulations.

1707
01:36:58,438 --> 01:37:01,064
Bonnie, make him give us a deal.
We want a home.

1708
01:37:01,232 --> 01:37:03,233
We're tired of shopping everything around.

1709
01:37:03,401 --> 01:37:05,694
BONNIE: I thought that's how
you guys like to do business.

1710
01:37:05,904 --> 01:37:07,571
Well, we changed our minds.

1711
01:37:08,823 --> 01:37:09,907
I'll talk to you later.

1712
01:37:11,409 --> 01:37:13,577
Levison says you're
going out of town tomorrow.

1713
01:37:14,245 --> 01:37:16,079
For the weekend.

1714
01:37:16,748 --> 01:37:20,000
Are you going with someone
named June something?

1715
01:37:20,752 --> 01:37:22,336
Yes.

1716
01:37:22,795 --> 01:37:27,132
You took her to a party, Griffin,
with several hundred of my best friends.

1717
01:37:27,342 --> 01:37:29,259
GRIFFIN:
She's recently widowed.

1718
01:37:29,427 --> 01:37:31,845
You weren't in town, so I took her.

1719
01:37:33,097 --> 01:37:36,016
And now you're taking her
to Mexico for the weekend.

1720
01:37:37,727 --> 01:37:39,853
ERIC: Let's get out of here.
Mom and Dad are fighting.

1721
01:37:40,021 --> 01:37:43,941
Guys, have your lawyer give me a call.

1722
01:37:44,108 --> 01:37:46,109
- You've got a deal.
ERIC & CARL: Yes!

1723
01:37:46,319 --> 01:37:48,195
Let's get out
before he changes his mind.

1724
01:37:48,363 --> 01:37:50,030
We have witnesses.

1725
01:38:03,044 --> 01:38:04,795
Have a good trip.

1726
01:38:11,803 --> 01:38:14,388
MAN [OVER LOUDSPEAKER]:
The white zone is for immediate loading...

1727
01:38:14,556 --> 01:38:17,182
...and unloading of passengers only.

1728
01:38:17,392 --> 01:38:18,642
No parking.

1729
01:38:18,851 --> 01:38:24,314
Do not leave your car unattended
due to the current security alert.

1730
01:38:24,524 --> 01:38:28,986
All unattended cars may be towed away
immediately.

1731
01:38:29,153 --> 01:38:30,529
For your safety...

1732
01:38:30,697 --> 01:38:32,698
- Uh, did you bring your passport?
- Yeah.

1733
01:38:32,865 --> 01:38:35,492
You wanna hear something funny?
I forgot mine.

1734
01:38:35,660 --> 01:38:36,743
Oh.

1735
01:38:36,911 --> 01:38:39,162
- We have to go back and get it.
GRIFFIN: So stupid of me.

1736
01:38:39,330 --> 01:38:41,873
- We'll miss the plane.
- We'll never make another plane.

1737
01:38:42,041 --> 01:38:43,500
Damn it!

1738
01:38:44,002 --> 01:38:46,336
It's all right.
Anyway, I got a better idea.

1739
01:38:46,504 --> 01:38:49,047
- Do you like the desert?
- I've never been to the desert.

1740
01:38:49,215 --> 01:38:51,341
Never been to the desert?
I know this hideaway...

1741
01:38:51,509 --> 01:38:52,843
...in Desert Hot Springs.

1742
01:38:53,011 --> 01:38:56,680
We'll go there. It's a two-hour drive.
I know the people. We'll call ahead.

1743
01:38:56,848 --> 01:38:58,515
Are we hiding?

1744
01:38:58,725 --> 01:39:02,060
Yeah. Yeah. We're hiding.
We're hiding from everybody.

1745
01:39:04,022 --> 01:39:06,398
You'll like it there.
It'll remind you of Iceland.

1746
01:39:20,872 --> 01:39:22,331
[RATTLES]

1747
01:39:39,057 --> 01:39:43,226
Evening, Mr. M. You're all checked in.
Capone Villa. You know where it is.

1748
01:39:43,436 --> 01:39:45,854
GRIFFIN: Yep. Thanks, Walter.
- You're welcome.

1749
01:40:12,882 --> 01:40:15,592
Hey, look.
The water looks like it's steaming.

1750
01:40:15,760 --> 01:40:18,136
Comes out of the ground that way.

1751
01:40:40,118 --> 01:40:42,494
There aren't many people around.

1752
01:40:43,121 --> 01:40:45,163
Well, they're fully booked, actually.

1753
01:40:45,415 --> 01:40:47,457
There's 50 rooms, 100 people.

1754
01:40:47,625 --> 01:40:49,543
Where are they all?

1755
01:40:50,128 --> 01:40:51,837
Hiding.

1756
01:40:52,088 --> 01:40:54,131
WAITER:
Ahem. Sir?

1757
01:40:54,549 --> 01:40:56,675
Couple of Banning Springs water please.

1758
01:40:56,926 --> 01:40:58,635
WAITER:
Right away, Mr. M.

1759
01:41:01,305 --> 01:41:03,724
Do places like this really exist?

1760
01:41:05,309 --> 01:41:06,935
Only in the movies.

1761
01:41:37,675 --> 01:41:40,761
JUNE:
Tell me about the movies you make.

1762
01:41:41,012 --> 01:41:42,679
GRIFFIN:
Why?

1763
01:41:43,181 --> 01:41:47,350
Because I want to know what you do.

1764
01:41:48,352 --> 01:41:54,191
Well, I listen to stories and decide
if they'll make good movies or not.

1765
01:41:54,525 --> 01:41:56,735
I get 125 phone calls a day.

1766
01:41:56,986 --> 01:42:00,572
And if I let that slip to 100...

1767
01:42:00,782 --> 01:42:04,117
...I know I'm not doing my job.

1768
01:42:04,285 --> 01:42:05,702
JUNE:
Oh.

1769
01:42:06,496 --> 01:42:09,790
Everyone that calls,
they wanna know one thing.

1770
01:42:10,583 --> 01:42:13,877
They want me to say yes to them
and make their movie.

1771
01:42:14,128 --> 01:42:17,130
If I say "Yes, I'll make the movie,"
they think come New Years...

1772
01:42:17,298 --> 01:42:21,802
...it's just gonna be them and
Jack Nicholson on the slopes of Aspen.

1773
01:42:22,553 --> 01:42:24,513
That's what they think.

1774
01:42:27,141 --> 01:42:28,892
Problem is...

1775
01:42:29,060 --> 01:42:33,730
...I can only say yes... My studio
can only say yes 12 times a year.

1776
01:42:33,898 --> 01:42:38,568
And collectively,
we hear about 50,000 stories a year.

1777
01:42:38,778 --> 01:42:40,737
So it's hard.

1778
01:42:43,074 --> 01:42:45,951
And I guess sometimes I'm not nice...

1779
01:42:47,453 --> 01:42:49,454
...and make enemies.

1780
01:42:50,915 --> 01:42:53,416
And that's what I was to David.

1781
01:42:54,252 --> 01:42:55,836
Enemy.

1782
01:42:56,587 --> 01:42:59,172
Was his story one of the 12?

1783
01:42:59,423 --> 01:43:01,258
No, it wasn't.

1784
01:43:01,926 --> 01:43:03,134
Why?

1785
01:43:03,344 --> 01:43:08,056
It lacks certain elements that we need
to market a film successfully.

1786
01:43:08,599 --> 01:43:10,642
What elements?

1787
01:43:12,770 --> 01:43:17,774
Suspense, laughter, violence.

1788
01:43:19,569 --> 01:43:21,945
Hope, heart.

1789
01:43:24,282 --> 01:43:26,700
Nudity, sex.

1790
01:43:28,286 --> 01:43:29,786
Happy endings.

1791
01:43:31,372 --> 01:43:33,999
Mainly happy endings.

1792
01:43:37,295 --> 01:43:39,129
What about reality?

1793
01:43:40,840 --> 01:43:42,716
You're not from Iceland, are you?

1794
01:43:44,677 --> 01:43:46,636
Did I say that?

1795
01:43:47,763 --> 01:43:49,055
Hmm.

1796
01:43:49,974 --> 01:43:53,977
Why don't you put me in the hot springs
and see if I melt?

1797
01:43:55,479 --> 01:43:58,607
[MOANING AND PANTING]

1798
01:44:42,234 --> 01:44:43,777
GRIFFIN:
I love you.

1799
01:44:44,028 --> 01:44:47,948
JUNE:
I know. I know.

1800
01:44:55,373 --> 01:44:57,457
I know.

1801
01:44:58,084 --> 01:45:00,043
There's something you have to know.

1802
01:45:00,211 --> 01:45:03,088
- I love you. I know I love you.
- Something I have to tell you.

1803
01:45:03,255 --> 01:45:05,173
That's all I need.

1804
01:45:05,383 --> 01:45:06,925
Nothing can change that.

1805
01:45:07,176 --> 01:45:08,593
June.

1806
01:45:08,803 --> 01:45:10,553
- David's death.
- No. Shh.

1807
01:45:10,721 --> 01:45:12,597
It's in the past.

1808
01:45:12,807 --> 01:45:15,809
Don't. Don't. It's another life.

1809
01:45:16,060 --> 01:45:19,062
I have to tell you something.
Something you have to know.

1810
01:45:19,271 --> 01:45:23,191
Don't, don't, don't say anymore. Don't.

1811
01:45:23,567 --> 01:45:25,610
- I was responsible.
- I love you. Don't.

1812
01:45:25,820 --> 01:45:28,905
- It was my fault.
- Don't say that.

1813
01:45:29,115 --> 01:45:33,076
Don't, don't, don't. I love you.

1814
01:46:51,489 --> 01:46:52,697
MASSEUSE:
Mr. M?

1815
01:46:53,074 --> 01:46:54,949
Mr. M, sorry to disturb you.

1816
01:46:55,117 --> 01:46:57,368
There's a telephone call
and it sounds important.

1817
01:46:57,536 --> 01:46:59,412
- Who is it?
- A Mr. Dick Mellen.

1818
01:46:59,580 --> 01:47:01,539
He says he's your lawyer.

