01:49:39,782 --> 01:49:41,991
OFFICER:
Number 1, step forward.

1865
01:49:42,284 --> 01:49:44,994
Make a quarter turn to the right.

1866
01:49:45,704 --> 01:49:48,206
- Are those prescription glasses?
AVERY: You can't ask her that.

1867
01:49:48,374 --> 01:49:50,083
- Fine.
- It's very hard, you know.

1868
01:49:50,292 --> 01:49:53,127
- Oh, yeah. I know.
OFFICER: Number 2, take one step forward.

1869
01:49:53,337 --> 01:49:56,506
- I wouldn't wanna pick the wrong one.
- No. God forbid.

1870
01:49:57,049 --> 01:49:58,341
BROOM:
You just take your time.

1871
01:49:58,509 --> 01:50:01,552
AVERY: Oh, I know.
Anybody look, uh, vaguely familiar?

1872
01:50:01,762 --> 01:50:03,346
OFFICER:
Take a quarter turn to the left.

1873
01:50:03,514 --> 01:50:05,098
[MUTTERS]

1874
01:50:05,266 --> 01:50:07,016
OFFICER: Face forward.
AVERY: Take your time.

1875
01:50:07,184 --> 01:50:09,435
OFFICER: Step back into position.
Number 3, take one step.

1876
01:50:09,603 --> 01:50:11,187
WITNESS: This is not easy.
AVERY: I know.

1877
01:50:11,355 --> 01:50:13,606
GIRARD: It never is.
WITNESS: I mean, I am trying.

1878
01:50:13,816 --> 01:50:15,566
AVERY:
Yes. Just take your time.

1879
01:50:15,734 --> 01:50:18,069
WITNESS: And I did see him clearly.
OFFICER: Face forward.

1880
01:50:18,237 --> 01:50:19,529
Make a quarter turn to the left.

1881
01:50:19,697 --> 01:50:20,989
[WITNESS SIGHS]

1882
01:50:23,075 --> 01:50:25,368
OFFICER: Step back as...
WITNESS: No, no, no. I don't know.

1883
01:50:25,619 --> 01:50:26,911
WITNESS: Well.
AVERY: Look hard.

1884
01:50:27,121 --> 01:50:31,582
- Look really... Take a good look.
WITNESS: No. I did, I did, I am. Um...

1885
01:50:31,792 --> 01:50:34,002
Could I see, um...

1886
01:50:34,962 --> 01:50:36,921
...Number 3 again?
GIRARD: Call Number 3.

1887
01:50:37,131 --> 01:50:39,173
AVERY: Wait a minute, wait a minute.
- Um, could I...?

1888
01:50:39,383 --> 01:50:41,676
GIRARD: Could she call her own numbers?
- Excuse me.

1889
01:50:41,885 --> 01:50:45,513
GIRARD: Maybe she wants to see again.
OFFICER: Number 5, take one step forward.

1890
01:50:45,681 --> 01:50:47,015
AVERY: Listen...
WITNESS: Excuse me.

1891
01:50:47,182 --> 01:50:48,266
AVERY:
Number 5.

1892
01:50:48,475 --> 01:50:51,060
GIRARD: Susan, I think she can call
who she's interested in.

1893
01:50:51,228 --> 01:50:54,981
AVERY: You're absolutely right.
- No, the other one. That one.

1894
01:50:55,149 --> 01:50:56,733
GIRARD: By the number.
AVERY: Which one?

1895
01:50:56,900 --> 01:51:00,486
WITNESS: Oh, um, uh, it's not Number 6.
- Not Number 6.

1896
01:51:00,654 --> 01:51:02,280
AVERY: How about Number 5?
WITNESS: Three.

1897
01:51:02,489 --> 01:51:04,407
GIRARD: Three.
AVERY: What do you mean, Number 3?

1898
01:51:04,575 --> 01:51:06,909
GIRARD: She can request who she wants.
AVERY: Just a second.

1899
01:51:07,077 --> 01:51:08,619
You wanna see what number?

1900
01:51:08,787 --> 01:51:12,832
WITNESS: Him! That's him.
I'd swear on my mother's grave.

1901
01:51:13,042 --> 01:51:15,418
GIRARD: Number 3.
I think we're concluded, Ms. Avery.

1902
01:51:15,586 --> 01:51:18,087
- The one, Number 3.
GIRARD: Number 3. On her mother's grave.

1903
01:51:18,255 --> 01:51:19,756
WITNESS: Yes.
AVERY: Number 3?

1904
01:51:20,257 --> 01:51:22,175
Number 3.
I think we heard what she said.

1905
01:51:22,384 --> 01:51:24,927
- Yeah, I would say so.
OFFICER: Okay, Doug, take them out.

1906
01:51:25,095 --> 01:51:28,014
GIRARD: Number 3, thank you.
AVERY: Just relax. You're in a chair.

1907
01:51:28,682 --> 01:51:30,725
- Ma'am, may I be personal?
- Yes.

1908
01:51:30,893 --> 01:51:32,643
Where the fuck is your mother buried?

1909
01:51:32,811 --> 01:51:33,853
[CHUCKLES]

1910
01:51:34,021 --> 01:51:36,439
AVERY: Let's get out of here.
- Let's get out of this sauna.

1911
01:51:36,607 --> 01:51:38,483
[SIREN WAILING]

1912
01:51:41,445 --> 01:51:45,031
I don't know who got to that witness,
but she sure wrapped up my case.

1913
01:51:45,240 --> 01:51:48,117
- You're a lucky man, Mr. Mill.
- Goddamn it, no ramp again.

1914
01:51:48,327 --> 01:51:49,702
Witnesses can't be relied on.

1915
01:51:49,912 --> 01:51:53,247
Remember Witness for the Prosecution,
Marlene Dietrich and Tyrone Power?

1916
01:51:53,457 --> 01:51:56,042
That's it. You're free as a bird.
No witness, no crime.

1917
01:51:56,251 --> 01:51:58,753
That Avery woman thinks
you just got away with murder.

1918
01:51:58,921 --> 01:52:01,214
Everybody does, Mr. Mill.

1919
01:52:15,896 --> 01:52:17,897
[PRISON CELL DOOR SLAMS]

1920
01:52:48,637 --> 01:52:53,391
Our Father, who art in heaven,
hallowed by thy name.

1921
01:52:53,600 --> 01:52:58,438
Thy kingdom come, thy will be done,
on earth as it is in heaven.

1922
01:52:58,897 --> 01:53:02,150
Give us this day our daily bread...

1923
01:53:02,359 --> 01:53:05,278
...and forgive us our trespasses...

1924
01:54:43,835 --> 01:54:47,838
You've made a wonderful movie.
It's perfect.

1925
01:54:48,048 --> 01:54:50,841
It's Oscar time, Larry.

1926
01:54:55,931 --> 01:54:58,891
- What?
- We're too late. Come on.

1927
01:54:59,101 --> 01:55:01,394
I gotta get the door open.

1928
01:55:02,771 --> 01:55:04,272
Come on.

1929
01:55:07,526 --> 01:55:09,819
- Hey, hey, hey!
- Get back!

1930
01:55:10,988 --> 01:55:12,989
[ALARM BLARING]

1931
01:55:28,046 --> 01:55:31,257
Oh. What took you so long?

1932
01:55:31,466 --> 01:55:32,925
Traffic was a bitch.

1933
01:55:43,520 --> 01:55:44,854
LEVY:
It's outstanding.

1934
01:55:45,063 --> 01:55:48,482
- The audience is gonna love it.
- You sold it out.

1935
01:55:48,650 --> 01:55:52,194
How could you let him sell you out?
What about truth? What about reality?

1936
01:55:52,362 --> 01:55:55,114
What about the way
the old ending tested in Canoga Park?

1937
01:55:55,324 --> 01:55:56,657
Everybody hated it.

1938
01:55:56,867 --> 01:55:59,869
We reshot it. Now everybody loves it.
That's reality.

1939
01:56:00,037 --> 01:56:02,830
BONNIE: You had an ending which was true.
You didn't give it a chance.

1940
01:56:02,998 --> 01:56:06,417
Who is this person? Does she know
anything about working with grown-ups?

1941
01:56:06,627 --> 01:56:08,794
Bonnie, goddamn it, goddamn it.

1942
01:56:09,004 --> 01:56:11,964
This is a hit.
This is what we're here for.

1943
01:56:12,174 --> 01:56:14,216
Yeah, well, it didn't have
to end this way.

1944
01:56:14,426 --> 01:56:17,720
LEVY: I want you out of here.
CIVELLA: Good thinking, Larry.

1945
01:56:17,929 --> 01:56:19,930
I'm going over your head, Larry.

1946
01:56:20,140 --> 01:56:22,433
Bonnie, you're fired.

1947
01:56:24,144 --> 01:56:25,478
Fuck you.

1948
01:56:25,687 --> 01:56:28,481
LEVY: It takes more to make it
in this business than a dirty mouth.

1949
01:56:28,649 --> 01:56:30,524
The campaign.

1950
01:56:52,631 --> 01:56:53,964
GAME VOICE:
Two points.

1951
01:56:59,262 --> 01:57:01,514
Celia, it's important.
I need to talk to him now.

1952
01:57:01,723 --> 01:57:03,474
- No, Bonnie, he's very busy.
- Please.

1953
01:57:03,642 --> 01:57:05,643
- No, you... Bonnie.
- Please, it's me, Bonnie.

1954
01:57:05,852 --> 01:57:08,062
- We're friends.
CELIA: Bonnie, you don't understand.

1955
01:57:08,271 --> 01:57:12,942
- I am not just me, I'm also the job.
- Please. Please. Please.

1956
01:57:13,151 --> 01:57:18,155
Oh, honey. All right, all right.
I'll try, okay?

1957
01:57:20,617 --> 01:57:22,535
GAME VOICE:
Three points.

1958
01:57:22,911 --> 01:57:26,497
- Great shot.
- Oh, Walter, stop that nonsense.

1959
01:57:26,707 --> 01:57:29,458
Griffin, it's Bonnie.

1960
01:57:29,668 --> 01:57:31,502
She's here.

1961
01:57:33,422 --> 01:57:35,423
GAME VOICE:
Great shot.

1962
01:57:36,133 --> 01:57:37,258
Levy fired her?

1963
01:57:37,467 --> 01:57:39,885
CELIA:
Yes, sir. I guess he did.

1964
01:57:41,388 --> 01:57:43,472
Well, I can't see her now.

1965
01:57:43,932 --> 01:57:46,225
I promised I'd be home early.

1966
01:57:47,519 --> 01:57:48,936
Tell her I'll get back to her.

1967
01:57:49,146 --> 01:57:51,689
Walter, get your foot
off the fucking couch.

1968
01:57:51,898 --> 01:57:52,982
Tell her yourself.

1969
01:57:53,150 --> 01:57:56,152
- Yes. Okay, well, could you hold, please?
- Griffin. Griffin.

1970
01:57:56,319 --> 01:57:57,403
I have to talk to you.

1971
01:57:57,612 --> 01:57:58,946
- Please!
JAN: It's very important.

1972
01:57:59,114 --> 01:58:03,033
- Griffin, please. Can we talk about it?
- Bonnie, you'll land on your feet. I know it.

1973
01:58:03,201 --> 01:58:06,078
- You're a survivor.
- It's Larry Levy's office. It's important.

1974
01:58:06,288 --> 01:58:08,289
Oh, put it in the front seat.

1975
01:58:08,623 --> 01:58:11,167
Give it a minute and
transfer it to the car phone.

1976
01:58:12,294 --> 01:58:14,378
[SOBBING]

1977
01:58:21,845 --> 01:58:23,471
[CAR PHONE RINGS]

1978
01:58:23,638 --> 01:58:26,682
GRIFFIN: Yeah?
JAN: Griffin, I have Larry Levy on the line.

1979
01:58:26,850 --> 01:58:29,226
GRIFFIN: Larry, how'd the screening go?
How's my new ending?

1980
01:58:29,394 --> 01:58:31,937
LEVY [ON PHONE]: Fantastic. Fantastic.
Worked like gangbusters.

1981
01:58:32,147 --> 01:58:36,108
- That's why you get the big bucks, Griff.
- Yeah, yeah. Stop kissing my ass, Larry.

1982
01:58:36,318 --> 01:58:39,195
- What? Can't this wait?
- I don't think it should. This is hot.

1983
01:58:39,362 --> 01:58:41,697
I got a writer who's got a pitch
you ought to hear.

1984
01:58:41,865 --> 01:58:44,200
It's something we should go for.
It's a great idea.

1985
01:58:44,367 --> 01:58:47,870
- Yeah? Who's the writer?
- I'll put him on the speaker. Hold on.

1986
01:58:48,038 --> 01:58:49,663
WRITER [ON PHONE]:
Hi, Griff. Remember me?

1987
01:58:49,831 --> 01:58:53,167
I'm the asshole who used to be
in the postcard business.

1988
01:58:53,376 --> 01:58:55,002
- You?
- Yeah, that's right.

1989
01:58:55,212 --> 01:58:57,671
The king of suspense himself.
You remember me?

1990
01:58:57,881 --> 01:58:59,715
I haven't heard from you in a while.

1991
01:58:59,925 --> 01:59:02,384
Well, I've been busy.
I've been writing a script.

1992
01:59:02,552 --> 01:59:04,261
- I got inspired.
LEVY: Give him the pitch.

1993
01:59:04,471 --> 01:59:06,430
You'll love this, Griffin. It's great.

1994
01:59:06,640 --> 01:59:09,391
WRITER: All right, it's a Hollywood story,
Griff. A real thriller.

1995
01:59:09,601 --> 01:59:12,895
It's about a shit-bag producer
studio exec...

1996
01:59:13,063 --> 01:59:16,440
...who murders a writer
he thinks is harassing him.

1997
01:59:16,650 --> 01:59:19,568
Problem is, he kills the wrong writer.

1998
01:59:19,778 --> 01:59:23,072
Now he's got to deal with blackmail
as well as the cops.

1999
01:59:23,281 --> 01:59:27,201
But here's the switch.
The son of a bitch, he gets away with it.

2000
01:59:27,369 --> 01:59:29,745
